# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fortran
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fortran/1200-fifth] The corner of the complex at 5th Avenue and University Street was the site of the Seattle Ice Arena from 1915 to 1963.
[src:fortran/1250-rené-lévesque] This 47-story skyscraper was designed by Kohn Pedersen Fox Associates and completed in 1992.
[src:fortran/1250-rené-lévesque] It was constructed between 1988 and 1992 as a project led by IBM and Marathon Realty with an investment of $250 million to consolidate IBM’s operations in Montreal, relocating 1,000 employees from Place Ville Marie.
[src:fortran/1250-rené-lévesque] The building’s location in downtown Montreal serves as a visual boundary between the commercial center and the historically residential west side, a concept inspired by KPF’s Westend Tower in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:fortran/1250-rené-lévesque] It is located next to Bell Centre and Windsor Station, and is connected to the Bonaventure metro station and Montreal’s Underground City.
[src:fortran/1250-rené-lévesque] The building’s architecture combines postmodern and neo-modern styles.
[src:fortran/1250-rené-lévesque] Its east and west facades differ distinctly: the west facade is a granite-clad wall with square windows and irregular setbacks, facing the residential periphery, while the east facade features a curved glass curtain wall facing the city center, giving a light, suspended effect.
[src:fortran/1250-rené-lévesque] A spire extends along the building’s north side, reaching 31 meters beyond the rooftop, aligning with Mount Royal's peak elevation.
[src:fortran/1250-rené-lévesque] Inside, a four-story atrium with a bamboo winter garden, food court, and conference rooms creates a welcoming space.
[src:fortran/1250-rené-lévesque] The building connects to Montreal’s Underground City and Bonaventure metro station.
[src:fortran/1250-rené-lévesque] Initially intended to be positioned at the edge of downtown Montreal, further development has caused 1250 René-Lévesque to be incorporated into a larger commercial area.
[src:fortran/1250-rené-lévesque] The smaller buildings to the west create a staircase effect, guiding the eye from the commercial core toward 1250 René-Lévesque.
[src:fortran/1250-rené-lévesque] Major tenants include IBM, Air Liquide, PwC, Deutsche Bank, PSP Investments, and many others in financial, technology, and consulting industries.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] The **history of the Berkeley Software Distribution** began in the 1970s when University of California, Berkeley received a copy of Unix.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Professors and students at the university began adding software to the operating system and released it as BSD to select universities.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Since it contained proprietary Unix code, it originally had to be distributed subject to AT&T licenses.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] The bundled software from AT&T was then rewritten and released as free software under the BSD license.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] However, this resulted in a lawsuit with Unix System Laboratories, the AT&T subsidiary responsible for Unix.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Eventually, in the 1990s, the final versions of BSD were publicly released without any proprietary licenses, which led to many descendants of the operating system that are still maintained today.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] The earliest distributions of Unix from Bell Labs in the 1970s included the source code to the operating system, allowing researchers at universities to modify and extend Unix.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] The operating system arrived at Berkeley in 1974, at the request of computer science professor Bob Fabry who had been on the program committee for the Symposium on Operating Systems Principles where Unix was first presented.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] A PDP-11/45 was bought to run the system, but for budgetary reasons, this machine was shared with the mathematics and statistics groups at Berkeley, who used RSTS, so that Unix only ran on the machine eight hours per day (sometimes during the day, sometimes during the night).
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] A larger PDP-11/70 was installed at Berkeley the following year, using money from the Ingres database project.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Also in 1975, Ken Thompson took a sabbatical from Bell Labs and came to Berkeley as a visiting professor.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] He helped to install Version 6 Unix and started working on a Pascal implementation for the system.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Graduate students Chuck Haley and Bill Joy improved Thompson's Pascal and implemented an improved text editor, ex.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Other universities became interested in the software at Berkeley, and so in 1977 Joy started compiling the first Berkeley Software Distribution (1BSD), which was released on March 9, 1978.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] 1BSD was an add-on to Version 6 Unix rather than a complete operating system in its own right.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] The Second Berkeley Software Distribution (2BSD), released in May 1979, included updated versions of the 1BSD software as well as two new programs by Joy that persist on Unix systems to this day: the vi text editor (a visual version of ex) and the C shell.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Some 75 copies of 2BSD were sent out by Bill Joy.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] A further feature was a networking package called Berknet, developed by Eric Schmidt as part of his master's thesis work, that could connect up to twenty-six computers and provided email and file transfer.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] 2.9BSD from 1983 included code from 4.1cBSD, and was the first release that was a full OS (a modified V7 Unix) rather than a set of applications and patches.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] The most recent release, **2.11BSD**, was first issued in 1991.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Unlike the previous releases, it required split instruction/data space, to accommodate the ever-increasing size of its utility programs.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] In the 21st century, maintenance updates from volunteers continued: patch ***#499*** was released on January 2, 2026.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] A DEC VAX computer was installed at Berkeley in 1978.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] The port of Version 7 Unix to the VAX architecture, UNIX/32V, did not take advantage of the VAX's virtual memory capabilities, which were necessary to run large programs such as Franz Lisp.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] The kernel of 32V was largely rewritten by Berkeley graduate student Özalp Babaoğlu to include a virtual memory implementation, and a complete operating system including the new kernel, ports of the 2BSD utilities to the VAX, and the utilities from 32V was released as 3BSD at the end of 1979.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] 3BSD was also alternatively called Virtual VAX/UNIX or VMUNIX (for Virtual Memory Unix), and BSD kernel images were normally called `/vmunix` until 4.4BSD.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] The success of 3BSD was a major factor in the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency's (DARPA) decision to fund Berkeley's Computer Systems Research Group (CSRG), which would develop a standard Unix platform for future DARPA research in the VLSI Project.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] 4BSD (November 1980) offered a number of enhancements over 3BSD, notably job control in the previously released csh, delivermail (the ancestor of sendmail), "reliable" signals, and the Curses programming library.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] 4.1BSD (June 1981) was a response to criticisms of BSD's performance relative to the dominant VAX operating system, VMS.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] The 4.1BSD kernel was systematically tuned up by Bill Joy until it could perform as well as VMS on several benchmarks.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] The release would have been called *5BSD*, but after objections from AT&T the name was changed; AT&T feared confusion with AT&T's UNIX System V.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Several tapes have turned up, all with a label that says 4.1BSD, yet differences between the tapes are present.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] The software development that would lead from 4.1BSD to 4.2BSD was funded from sources including ARPA, Order Number 4031, Contract N00039-82-C-0235 which was in effect at least from November 15, 1981 through September 30, 1983.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] 4.2BSD (August 1983) would take over two years to implement and contained several major overhauls.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Back at Bell Labs, 4.1cBSD became the basis of the 8th Edition of Research Unix, and a commercially supported version was available from mt Xinu.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] The committee met from April 1981 to June 1983.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Apart from the Fast File System, several features from outside contributors were accepted, including disk quotas.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Sun Microsystems provided testing on its Motorola 68000 machines prior to release, improving portability of the system.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Sun hardware support is plainly visible in the 4.1c BSD artifacts in the CSRG ISO.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] The official 4.2BSD release came in August 1983.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] It was notable as the first version released after the 1982 departure of Bill Joy to co-found Sun Microsystems; Mike Karels and Marshall Kirk McKusick took on leadership roles within the project from that point forward.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] On a lighter note, it also marked the debut of BSD's daemon mascot in a drawing by John Lasseter that appeared on the cover of the printed manuals distributed by USENIX.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Its main changes were to improve the performance of many of the new contributions of 4.2BSD that had not been as heavily tuned as the 4.1BSD code.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Prior to the release, BSD's implementation of TCP/IP had diverged considerably from BBN's official implementation.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] After several months of testing, DARPA determined that the 4.2BSD version was superior and would remain in 4.3BSD.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] After 4.3BSD, it was determined that BSD would move away from the aging VAX platform.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] The Power 6/32 platform (codenamed "Tahoe") developed by Computer Consoles Inc. seemed promising at the time, but was abandoned by its developers shortly thereafter.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Nonetheless, the **4.3BSD-Tahoe** port (June 1988) proved valuable, as it led to a separation of machine-dependent and machine-independent code in BSD which would improve the system's future portability.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Apart from portability, the CSRG worked on an implementation of the OSI network protocol stack, improvements to the kernel virtual memory system and (with Van Jacobson of LBL) new TCP/IP algorithms to accommodate the growth of the Internet.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Until then, all versions of BSD incorporated proprietary AT&T Unix code and were, therefore, subject to an AT&T software license.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Source code licenses had become very expensive and several outside parties had expressed interest in a separate release of the networking code, which had been developed entirely outside AT&T and would not be subject to the licensing requirement.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] This led to **Networking Release 1** (**Net/1**), which was made available to non-licensees of AT&T code and was freely redistributable under the terms of the BSD license.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] In August 2006, *InformationWeek* magazine rated 4.3BSD as the "Greatest Software Ever Written".
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] After Net/1, BSD developer Keith Bostic proposed that more non-AT&T sections of the BSD system be released under the same license as Net/1.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] To this end, he started a project to reimplement most of the standard Unix utilities without using the AT&T code.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] For example, vi, which had been based on the original Unix version of ed, was rewritten as nvi (new vi).
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Within eighteen months, all of the AT&T utilities had been replaced, and it was determined that only a few AT&T files remained in the kernel.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] These files were removed, and the result was the June 1991 release of **Networking Release 2** (**Net/2**), aka Network(ing) 2, a nearly complete operating system that was freely distributable.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Net/2 was the basis for two separate ports of BSD to the Intel 80386 architecture: the free 386BSD by William Jolitz and the proprietary BSD/386 (later renamed BSD/OS) by Berkeley Software Design (BSDi).
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] 386BSD itself was short-lived, but became the initial code base of the NetBSD and FreeBSD projects that were started shortly thereafter.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] BSDi soon found itself in legal trouble with AT&T's Unix System Laboratories (USL) subsidiary, then the owners of the System V copyright and the Unix trademark.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] BSDi* lawsuit was filed in April 1992 and led to an injunction on the distribution of Net/2 until the validity of USL's copyright claims on the source could be determined.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] The lawsuit slowed development of the free-software descendants of BSD for nearly two years while their legal status was in question, and as a result systems based on the Linux kernel, which did not have such legal ambiguity, gained greater support.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Although not released until 1992, development of 386BSD predated that of Linux.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Linus Torvalds has said that if 386BSD or the GNU kernel had been available at the time, he probably would not have created Linux.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] In August 1992, **4.4BSD-Alpha** was released, and in June 1993, **4.4BSD-Encumbered** was released only to USL licensees.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] The lawsuit was settled in January 1994, largely in Berkeley's favor.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Of the 18,000 files in the Berkeley distribution, only three had to be removed and 70 modified to show USL copyright notices.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] A further condition of the settlement was that USL would not file further lawsuits against users and distributors of the Berkeley-owned code in the upcoming 4.4BSD release.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] In March 1994, **4.4BSD-Lite** was released that no longer required a USL source license and also contained many other changes over the original 4.4BSD-Encumbered release.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] The final release from Berkeley was 1995's **4.4BSD-Lite Release 2**, after which the CSRG was dissolved and development of BSD at Berkeley ceased.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Since then, several variants based directly or indirectly on 4.4BSD-Lite (such as FreeBSD, NetBSD, OpenBSD and DragonFly BSD) have been maintained.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] In addition, the permissive nature of the BSD license has allowed many other operating systems, both free and proprietary, to incorporate BSD code.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] For example, Microsoft Windows has used BSD-derived code in its implementation of TCP/IP and bundles recompiled versions of BSD's command-line networking tools since Windows 2000.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Also Darwin, the system on which Apple's macOS is built, is a derivative of 4.4BSD-Lite2 and FreeBSD.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Various commercial Unix operating systems, such as Solaris, also contain varying amounts of BSD code.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] BSD has been the base of a large number of operating systems.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Most notable among these today are perhaps the major open source BSDs: FreeBSD, NetBSD and OpenBSD, which are all derived from 386BSD and 4.4BSD-Lite by various routes.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Both NetBSD and FreeBSD started life in 1993, initially derived from 386BSD, but in 1994 migrating to a 4.4BSD-Lite code base.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] A number of commercial operating systems are also partly or wholly based on BSD or its descendants, including Sun's SunOS and Apple Inc.'s macOS.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Most of the current BSD operating systems are open source and available for download, free of charge, under the BSD License, the most notable exception being macOS.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] They also generally use a monolithic kernel architecture, apart from macOS and DragonFly BSD which feature hybrid kernels.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] The various open source BSD projects generally develop the kernel and userland programs and libraries together, the source code being managed using a single central source repository.
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] In the past, BSD was also used as a basis for several proprietary versions of Unix, such as Sun's SunOS, Sequent's Dynix, NeXT's NeXTSTEP, DEC's Ultrix and OSF/1 AXP (now Tru64 UNIX).
[src:fortran/4-3bsd] Parts of NeXT's software became the foundation for macOS, among the most commercially successful BSD variants in the general market.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] 4chan was created as an unofficial English-language counterpart to the Japanese imageboard Futaba Channel, also known as 2chan, and its first boards were originally used for posting images and discussion related to anime.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] 4chan has often been the subject of media attention as a source of controversies, including the coordination of pranks and harassment against websites and Internet users, and the posting of illegal and offensive content as a result of its lax censorship and moderation policies.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] In 2008, *The Guardian* summarized the 4chan community as "lunatic, juvenile [...] brilliant, ridiculous and alarming".
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The majority of posting on 4chan takes place on imageboards, on which users have the ability to share images and create threaded discussions.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] As of August 2022, the site's homepage lists 75 imageboards and one Flash animation board.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Most boards have their own set of rules and are dedicated to a specific topic, including anime and manga, video games, music, literature, fitness, politics, and sports, among others.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Uniquely, the "Random" board—also known as /b/—has few rules.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] In 2008, 4chan was one of the Internet's busiest imageboards, according to the *Los Angeles Times*.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] 4chan's Alexa rank was 853 in March 2022, though it has been as high as 56.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] It is provided to its users free of charge and consumes a large amount of bandwidth; as a result, its financing has often been problematic.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Poole has acknowledged that donations alone could not keep the site online, and turned to advertising to help make ends meet.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] However, the explicit content hosted on 4chan has deterred businesses who do not want to be associated with the site's content.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] In January 2009, Poole signed a new deal with an advertising company; in February 2009, he was $20,000 in debt, and the site was continuing to lose money.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The 4chan servers were moved from Texas to California in August 2008, which upgraded the maximum bandwidth throughput of 4chan from 100 Mbit/s to 1 Gbit/s.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Unlike most web forums, 4chan does not have a registration system, allowing users to post anonymously.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Posting is ephemeral, as threads receiving recent replies are "bumped" to the top of their respective board and old threads are deleted as new ones are created.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Any nickname may be used when posting, even one that has been previously adopted, such as "Anonymous" or "moot".
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] In place of registration, 4chan has provided tripcodes as an optional form of authenticating a poster's identity.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] As making a post without filling in the "Name" field causes posts to be attributed to "Anonymous", general understanding on 4chan holds that Anonymous is not a single person but a collective (hive) of users.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Moderators generally post without a name even when performing sysop actions.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] A "capcode" may be used to attribute the post to "Anonymous ## Mod", although moderators often post without the capcode.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] In a 2011 interview on Nico Nico Douga, Poole explained that there are approximately 20 volunteer moderators active on 4chan.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] 4chan also has a junior moderation team, called "janitors", who may delete posts or images and suggest that the normal moderation team ban a user, but who cannot post with a capcode.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Revealing oneself as a janitor is grounds for immediate dismissal.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Gianluca Stringhini, an associate professor at Boston University College of Engineering, said in August 2024, "The only moderation on the platform appears to be for clearly illegal content, such as child pornography.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] 4chan has been the target of occasional denial of service attacks.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The site was launched as 4chan.net on October 1, 2003, by Christopher Poole, a then-15-year-old student from New York City using the online handle "moot".
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Poole had been a regular participant on Something Awful's subforum "Anime Death Tentacle Rape Whorehouse" (ADTRW), where many users were familiar with the Japanese imageboard format and Futaba Channel ("2chan.net").
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] When creating 4chan, Poole obtained Futaba Channel's open source code and translated the Japanese text into English using AltaVista's Babel Fish online translator.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] After the site's creation, Poole invited users from the ADTRW subforum, many of whom were dissatisfied with the site's moderation, to visit 4chan, which he advertised as an English-language counterpart to Futaba Channel and a place for Western fans to discuss anime and manga.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] At its founding, the site only hosted one board: /b/ (Anime/Random).
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Before the end of 2003, several new anime-related boards were added, including /h/ (Hentai), /c/ (Anime/Cute), /d/ (Hentai/Alternative), /w/ (Wallpapers/Anime), /y/ (Yaoi), and /a/ (Anime).
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] In the early days of the website, Poole hosted meetings from 2005 to 2008 in various locations to promote it, such as Otakon, that popularized some of the first 4chan-related memes.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Additionally, a lolicon board was created at /l/ (Lolikon), but was disabled following the posting of real-life child pornography and ultimately deleted in October 2004, after threats of legal action.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] In February 2004, GoDaddy suspended the 4chan.net domain, prompting Poole to move the site to its current domain at 4chan.org.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] On March 1, 2004, Poole announced that he lacked the funds to pay the month's server bill, but was able to continue operations after receiving a swarm of donations from users.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] In June 2004, 4chan experienced six weeks of downtime due to PayPal suspending 4chan's donations service after receiving complaints about the site's content.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Following 4chan's return, several non-anime related boards were introduced, including /k/ (Weapons), /o/ (Auto), and /v/ (Video Games).
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] In 2008, nine new boards were created, including the sports board at /sp/, the fashion board at /fa/ and the "Japan/General" (the name later changed to "Otaku Culture") board at /jp/.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] By this point, 4chan's culture had altered, moving away from the "early, more childish," humour, as evident by the likes of Project Chanology; trolling underwent a so-called "golden age" that took aim at American corporate media.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] In January 2011, Poole announced the deletion of the /r9k/ ("ROBOT9000") and /new/ (News) boards, saying that /new/ had become devoted to racist discussions, and /r9k/ no longer served its original purpose of being a test implementation of xkcd's ROBOT9000 script.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] In 2010, 4chan had implemented reCAPTCHA in an effort to thwart spam arising from JavaScript worms.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] By November 2011, 4chan made the transition to utilizing Cloudflare following a series of DDoS attacks.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The 4chan imageboards were rewritten in valid HTML5/CSS3 in May 2012 in an effort to improve client-side performance.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] On September 28, 2012, 4chan introduced a "4chan pass" that, when purchased, "allows users to bypass typing a reCAPTCHA verification when posting and reporting posts on the 4chan image boards"; the money raised from the passes to go towards supporting the site.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] On January 21, 2015, Poole stepped down as the site's administrator, citing stress from controversies such as Gamergate as the reason for his departure.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] On September 21, 2015, Poole announced that Hiroyuki Nishimura had purchased from him the ownership rights to 4chan, without disclosing the terms of the acquisition.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] In October 2016, it was reported that the site was facing financial difficulties that could lead to its closure or radical changes.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] In a post titled "Winter is Coming", Hiroyuki Nishimura explained, "We had tried to keep 4chan as is.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] I am sincerely sorry", citing server costs, infrastructure costs, and network fees.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] On November 17, 2018, it was announced that the site would be split into two, with the work-safe boards moved to a new domain, 4channel.org, while the NSFW boards would remain on the 4chan.org domain.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] In a series of posts on the topic, Nishimura explained that the split was due to 4chan being blacklisted by most advertising companies and that the new 4channel domain would allow for the site to receive advertisements by mainstream ad providers.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] All boards returned to the 4chan.org domain in December 2023 for unknown reasons, and 4channel.org now redirects to 4chan.org.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] In a 2020 interview with *Vice Media*, several current or past moderators spoke about what they perceived as racist intent behind the site's management.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] They alleged that a managing moderator, known online as RapeApe, was attempting to use the site as a recruitment tool for the alt-right, and that Nishimura was "hands-off, leaving moderation of the site primarily to RapeApe." Neither Nishimura nor RapeApe responded to these allegations.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Far-right extremism has been reported by public authorities, commentators and civil society groups as connected, in part, to 4chan, an association that had arisen by 2015.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] According to 4chan's filings to the New York Attorney General's Office, 4chan signed an agreement to pay RapeApe $3,000 a month for their services in 2015.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] By May 2022, that fee had risen to $4,400 a month.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The submitted documents also revealed RapeApe lamenting that 4chan was "getting the shaft" over the Buffalo terrorist attack and his attempt to persuade the advertising platform Bid.Glass to reverse their exit from the website.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] On April 14, 2025, 4chan was hacked by an anonymous user who later announced the hack on soyjak.party, a rival imageboard website with origins related to 4chan.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Source code and user logins of those who registered with emails were apparently acquired by the user and leaked online.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Additionally, the deleted /qa/ board was restored.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] On soyjak.party, information purporting to be from the hack was released, claiming "admin" level access, a lack of updates to the site since 2016, and identities of admins, among other claims.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] One of the last known posts made on 4chan before it was taken down was the "Chicken jockey!" quote, taken from *A Minecraft Movie*.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] In the days following the attacks, 4chan and Nishimura's official Twitter accounts released statements confirming that they would work to fix security vulnerabilities and return at a later date.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Due to its temporary unavailability, some users took to the site's Downdetector page, using its comment section as a temporary replacement for the website.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] On May 21, 2026, the /r/ Adult Requests board was deleted following claims of deepfaked nude photos of celebrities being requested on the /r/ board.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Poole concealed his real-life identity until it was revealed on July 9, 2008, in *The Wall Street Journal*.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Prior to that, he had used the alias "moot".
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] In April 2009, an open Internet poll conducted by *Time* magazine voted Poole as the world's most influential person of 2008.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The results were questioned even before the poll completed, as automated voting programs and manual ballot stuffing were used to influence the vote.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] 4chan's interference with the vote seemed increasingly likely, when it was found that reading the first letter of the first 21 candidates in the poll spelled out a phrase containing two 4chan memes: "mARBLECAKE.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] On September 12, 2009, Poole gave a talk regarding 4chan's reputation as a "Meme Factory" at the Paraflows Symposium in Vienna, Austria, which was part of the Paraflows 09 festival, themed *Urban Hacking: Cultural Jamming Strategies in the Risky Spaces of Modernity*.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] In this talk, Poole mainly attributed this both to the anonymous system and to the lack of data retention on the site ("The site has no memory.").
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] In April 2010, Poole testified in the trial *United States of America v.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] David Kernell* as a government witness, explaining the terminology used on 4chan to the prosecutor, ranging from "OP" to "lurker", as well as the nature of the data given to the FBI as part of the search warrant, including how users can be uniquely identified from site audit logs.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The "random" board, **/b/**, follows the design of Futaba Channel's Nijiura ("Random") board.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] It was the first board created, and has been described as 4chan's most popular board, accounting for 30% of site traffic in 2009.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The "no invasions" rule was added in late 2006, after /b/ users spent most of that summer "invading" *Habbo Hotel*.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The "no rules" policy also applies to actions of administrators and moderators, which means that users may be banned at any time, for any reason, including for no reason at all.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Due partially to its anonymous nature, board moderation is not always successful—indeed, the site's anti-child pornography rule is a subject of jokes on /b/.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Christopher Poole told *The New York Times*, in a discussion on the moderation of /b/, that "the power lies in the community to dictate its own standards" and that site staff simply provided a framework.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The humor of /b/'s many users, who refer to themselves as "/b/tards", is often incomprehensible to newcomers and outsiders, and is characterized by intricate inside jokes and dark comedy.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Users often refer to each other, and much of the outside world, as fags.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] They are often referred to by outsiders as trolls, who regularly act with the intention of "doing it for the lulz", a corruption of "LOL" used to denote amusement at another's expense.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] A significant amount of media coverage is in response to /b/'s culture, which has been characterized as adolescent, crude and spiteful, with one publication writing that their "bad behavior is encouraged by the site's total anonymity and the absence of an archive".
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Douglas cited Encyclopedia Dramatica's definition of /b/ as "the asshole of the Internets [*sic*]".
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Certain post numbers are sought after with a large amount of posting taking place to "GET" them.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] A "GET" occurs when a post's number ends in a special number, such as 12345678, 22222222, or every millionth post.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] A sign of 4chan's scaling, according to Poole, was when GETs lost meaning due to the high post rate resulting in a GET occurring every few weeks.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The *My Little Pony* board, **/mlp/**, titled as *Pony*, is dedicated to discussion of the animated television series *My Little Pony: Friendship Is Magic* and its associated fandom.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Created on February 16, 2012, the board was established by Poole in response to the growing popularity of pony-related content flooding other boards, particularly /co/ and /b/.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Along with the board's creation, Poole implemented "Global Rule 15" (GR15), which banned pony content outside of a few select boards, directing all such discussions to /mlp/.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The board became home to the "brony" fandom on 4chan, though many users on /mlp/ reject this label, preferring self-deprecating terms like *horsefuckers* or *ponyfags*.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Notable events include a 2013 Q&A with *Friendship Is Magic* creator Lauren Faust and the board's temporary merger with /pol/ on April 1, 2017, creating "/mlpol/".
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Despite the original series ending in 2019, /mlp/ continues to maintain an active community.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The board has been the subject of academic research regarding masculinity and online identity, particularly in a 2017 ethnographic study published in the journal *Sexualities* that examined how users construct collective identity around their interest in the show and its characters.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The music board, **/mu/**, is dedicated to the discussion of music artists, albums, genres, and instruments.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The board has gained notoriety for earnestly focusing upon and promoting challenging and otherwise obscure music.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Some common genres discussed on /mu/ include shoegaze, experimental hip hop, witch house, IDM, midwest emo, vaporwave, and K-pop.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] There is a significant overlap between user bases of /mu/ and music site Rate Your Music.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The board's culture has inspired many online music communities and meme pages on social media that emulate /mu/'s posting style.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Publications such as *Pitchfork* and *Entertainment Weekly* noted the board played a significant role in popularizing various music artists, such as Death Grips, Neutral Milk Hotel, Car Seat Headrest, and Have a Nice Life.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Prominent music critic Anthony Fantano began his career on /mu/ and developed a significant following there.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Some artists, like Zeal & Ardor and Conrad Tao, admitted to posting their music anonymously on /mu/ to get honest feedback, as well as find inspiration from the board.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] In particular, Zeal & Ardor said their sound, which mixes black metal with spirituals, came from suggestions by two users.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Andrew W.K. did a Q&A with the board's users in 2011, causing the servers to crash from the increased traffic.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Death Grips seeded various clues on /mu/ in 2012 about their then-upcoming albums *The Money Store* and *No Love Deep Web*.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] A rendition of "Royals" by Lorde appeared on /mu/ in 2012 before its official release, although she denied ever writing on the board in 2014.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Singer Lauren Mayberry shared on Twitter in 2015 a link to a thread on /mu/ about her band's song "Leave a Trace" to showcase what online misogyny looks like.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] An alleged unreleased Radiohead song, titled "Putting Ketchup in the Fridge" and "How Do You Sit Still", was initially reported as genuine by *NME* and *Spin* until CNN revealed it was a hoax promoted by the board's users.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The board has been acknowledged for sharing rare music recordings and unreleased materials, as well as finding albums thought to be lost.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Notable examples include the works of Duster, *D>E>A>T>H>M>E>T>A>L* by Panchiko, and *All Lights Fucked on the Hairy Amp Drooling* by Godspeed You!
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] This was described by NPR as resembling "a secret club of preservationists obsessed with the articulation of a near-dead language".
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The board has attracted further attention for various projects done by its users.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] A group called The Pablo Collective posted a 4-track remix album of Kanye West's *The Life of Pablo* titled *The Death of Pablo* to /mu/, claiming it was based on a recurring dream from one of the board's users.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] A role-playing game based on Neutral Milk Hotel's *In the Aeroplane Over the Sea*, designed with help from the board's users, received coverage from *Polygon* and *Pitchfork*.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Although there had previously been a strong left-libertarian contingent to 4chan activists, there was a gradual rightward turn on 4chan's politics board in the early-mid 2010s, with the fundamentalist approach to free speech contributing.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The board quickly attracted posters with a political persuasion that later would be described with a new term, the alt-right.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Media sources have characterized /pol/ as predominantly racist and sexist, with many of its posts taking an explicitly neo-Nazi bent.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The Southern Poverty Law Center regards /pol/'s rhetorical style as widely emulated by white supremacist websites such as *The Daily Stormer*; the *Stormer*'s editor, Andrew Anglin, concurred. /pol/ was where screenshots of Trayvon Martin's hacked social media accounts were initially posted.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The board's users have started antifeminist, homophobic, transphobic, and anti-Arab Twitter campaigns.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Many /pol/ users favored Donald Trump during his 2016 United States presidential campaign.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Both Trump and his son, Donald Trump Jr., appeared to acknowledge the support by tweeting /pol/-associated memes.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Upon his successful election, a /pol/ moderator embedded a pro-Trump video at the top of all of the board's pages.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] It became a popular gathering place for the controversial online *incel* community.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The "beta uprising" or "beta rebellion" meme, the idea of taking revenge against women, jocks and others perceived as the cause of incels' problems, was popularized on the subsection.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The perpetrator of the Toronto van attack referenced 4chan and an incel rebellion in a Facebook post he made prior to the attack, while praising self-identified incel Elliot Rodger, the killer behind the 2014 Isla Vista killings.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] He claims to have talked with both Christopher Harper-Mercer and Rodger on Reddit and 4chan and believes that he was part of a "beta uprising", also posting a message on 4chan about his intention the day before his attack.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] On July 21, 2023, an anonymous user posted a link to a self-made free and open source dating app, Duolicious, in a /soc/ thread, initially advertising it as an "experimental matchmaking algorithm".
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] In May 2024, the app went viral, briefly outranking mainstream apps including eHarmony on Google Play's "Top for $0" dating category despite the app's creator stating "it was only meant to be a meme app".
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Many of the earliest creepypastas (Internet horror-related legends) were created on /x/.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] After the 4chan post gained fame, several Internet users wrote horror stories relating to the Backrooms.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Many memes were created and shared across social media, further popularizing the creepypasta.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] American model Allison Harvard first gained notoriety in 2005 as an Internet meme on the /x/ board where she became known as Creepy Chan.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Known for her large eyes and peculiar interests like fascination with blood, photos she posted on her blog were widely circulated on the board.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] She gained mainstream notoriety in 2009 and again in 2011 by appearing on *America's Next Top Model*.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] She would visit /x/ after new episodes of America's Next Top Model would air to see what was being written about her and participate in the discussions.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The SCP Foundation, a fictional secret organization documented by the collaborative writing wiki project of the same name, originated on /x/ in 2007, when the first SCP file, SCP-173, was posted by an anonymous user.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Initially a stand-alone short story, many additional SCP files were created shortly after; these new SCPs copied SCP-173's style and were set within the same fictional universe.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] A stand-alone wiki was created in January 2008 on the EditThis wiki hosting service to display the SCP articles.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The EditThis website did not have moderators, or the ability to delete articles.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Members communicated through individual article talk pages and the /x/ board.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] /x/ was the first place where the 2015 viral video *11B-X-1371* was posted.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The board also contributed to investigating and popularizing the controversial *Sad Satan* video game.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] "[A] significant and influential element of contemporary internet culture", 4chan is responsible for many early memes and the site has received positive attention for its association with memes.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] 4chan and other websites, such as the satirical Encyclopedia Dramatica, have also contributed to the development of significant amounts of leetspeak.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] A lolcat is an image combining a photograph of a cat with solecistic text intended to contribute humour, widely popularized by 4chan in the form of a weekly post dedicated to them and a corresponding theme.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] In 2005, the installment of a word filter which changed "egg" to "duck", and thus "eggroll" to "duckroll", across 4chan led to a bait-and-switch meme in which users deceitfully linked to a picture of a duck on wheels.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] This was then modified into users linking to the music video for Rick Astley's 1987 song "Never Gonna Give You Up".
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] A link to the YouTube video of Tay Zonday's song "Chocolate Rain" was posted on /b/ on July 11, 2007, and then subsequently circulated by users, becoming a very popular internet meme.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The portion of the song in which Zonday turns away from the microphone, with a caption stating "I move away from the mic to breathe in", became an oft-repeated meme on 4chan and inspired remixes.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Fellow YouTuber Boxxy's popularity was also due in part to 4chan.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] In his American incarnation, Pedobear is an anthropomorphic bear child predator that is often used within the community to mock contributors showing a sexual interest in children.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Pedobear is one of the most popular memes on non-English imageboards, and has gained recognition across Europe, appearing in offline publications.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] It has been used as a symbol of pedophilia by Maltese graffiti vandals prior to a papal visit.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] 4chan has been labeled as the starting point of the Anonymous meme by The *Baltimore City Paper*, due to the norm of posts signed with the "Anonymous" moniker.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The *National Post*'s David George-Cosh said it has been "widely reported" that Anonymous is associated with 4chan and 711chan, as well as numerous Internet Relay Chat (IRC) channels.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Through its association with Anonymous, 4chan has become associated with Project Chanology, a worldwide protest against the Church of Scientology held by members of Anonymous.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] On January 15, 2008, a 4chan user posted to /b/, suggesting participants "do something big" against the Church of Scientology's website.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] This message resulted in the Church receiving threatening phone calls.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] It quickly grew into a large real-world protest.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Unlike previous Anonymous attacks, this action was characterized by 4chan memes, including rickrolls and Guy Fawkes masks.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The raid drew criticism from some 4chan users who felt it would bring the site undesirable attention.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The adult fandom and subculture dedicated to the children's animated television series *My Little Pony: Friendship Is Magic* began on the "Comics & Cartoons" (/co/) board of 4chan.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The show was first discussed with some interest around its debut in October 2010.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] The users of /co/ took a heightened interest in the show after a critical Cartoon Brew article was shared, resulting in praise for its plot, characters, and animation style.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Discussion of the show extended to /b/, eventually to a point of contention.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Discussion then spread forth to communities external to 4chan, including the establishment of the fan websites, causing the show to reach a wider audience across the internet.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Less than an hour later the post was photographed off the screen and framed by another user who posted another reply in the thread with a photo of the framed quote.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Later the user, after endorsement by other anonymous users in the thread, created an auction on eBay for the framed photo which quickly rose to high prices, culminating in a price of $90,900.
[src:fortran/4chan-p01] Pajeet, or Jeet is an invented term for Indian people, particularly adherents of Hinduism and Sikhism, originating on 4chan in 2015.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] Users of 4chan and other websites "raided" Hal Turner by launching denial-of-service attacks and prank calling his phone-in radio show during December 2006 and January 2007.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] The attacks caused Turner's website to go offline.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] This cost thousands of dollars in bandwidth bills according to Turner.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] In response, Turner sued 4chan, 7chan, and other websites; however, he lost his plea for an injunction and failed to receive letters from the court.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] KTTV Fox 11 aired a report on Anonymous, calling them a group of "hackers on steroids", "domestic terrorists", and collectively an "Internet hate machine" on July 26, 2007.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] Slashdot founder Rob Malda posted a comment made by another Slashdot user, Miang, stating that the story focused mainly on users of "4chan, 7chan and 420chan".
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] Miang claimed that the report "seems to confuse /b/ raids and motivational poster templates with a genuine threat to the American public", arguing that the "unrelated" footage of a van exploding shown in the report was to "equate anonymous posting with domestic terror".
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] On July 10, 2008, the swastika CJK unicode character (卐) appeared at the top of Google's Hot Trends list—a tally of the most used search terms in the United States—for several hours.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] It was later reported that the HTML numeric character reference for the symbol had been posted on /b/, with a request to perform a Google search for the string.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] A multitude of /b/ visitors followed the order and pushed the symbol to the top of the chart, though Google later removed the result.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] Mail account of Sarah Palin, Republican vice presidential candidate in the 2008 United States presidential election, was hacked by a 4chan user.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] The hacker posted the account's password on /b/, and screenshots from within the account to WikiLeaks.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] A /b/ user then logged in and changed the password, posting a screenshot of him sending an email to a friend of Palin's informing her of the new password on the /b/ thread.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] However, he forgot to blank out the password in the screenshot.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] A multitude of /b/ users attempted to log in with the new password, and the account was automatically locked out by Yahoo!.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] The incident was criticized by some /b/ users.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] We could have changed history and failed, epically." The FBI and Secret Service began investigating the incident shortly after its occurrence.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] On September 20 it was revealed they were questioning David Kernell, the son of Democratic Tennessee State Representative Mike Kernell.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] The stock price of Apple Inc. fell significantly in October 2008 after a hoax story was submitted to CNN's user-generated news site iReport.com claiming that company CEO Steve Jobs had suffered a major heart attack.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] The source of the story was traced back to 4chan.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] In May 2009, members of the site attacked YouTube, posting pornographic videos on the video-sharing platform under names of teenage celebrities.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] The attack spawned the popular Internet meme and catchphrase "I'm 12 years old and what is this?" as a response to a user comment on one such video.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] A 4chan member acknowledged being part of the attack, telling BBC News that it was in response to YouTube "deleting music".
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] In January 2010, members of the site attacked YouTube again in response to the suspension of YouTube user lukeywes1234 for failing to meet the minimum age requirement of thirteen.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] The videos uploaded by the user had apparently become popular with 4chan members, who subsequently became angered after the account was suspended and called for a new wave of pornographic videos to be uploaded to YouTube on January 6, 2010.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] Later the same year, 4chan made numerous disruptive pranks directed at singer Justin Bieber.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] The targeted websites usually went offline for a short period of time due to the attacks, before recovering.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] The website of the UK law firm ACS:Law, which was associated with an anti-piracy client, was affected by the cyber-attack.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] In retaliation for the initial attacks being called only a minor nuisance, Anonymous launched more attacks, bringing the site down yet again.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] After coming back up, the front page accidentally revealed a backup file of the entire website, which contained over 300 megabytes of private company emails, which were leaked to several torrents and across several sites on the Internet.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] It was suggested that the data leak could cost the law firm up to £500,000 in fines for breaching British Data Protection Laws.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] In January 2011, BBC News reported that the law firm announced they were to stop "chasing illegal file-sharers".
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] Head of ACS:Law Andrew Crossley in a statement to a court addressed issues which influenced the decision to back down "I have ceased my work ...
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] In August 2012, 4chan users attacked a third-party sponsored Mountain Dew campaign, *Dub the Dew*, where users were asked to submit and vote on name ideas for a green apple flavor of the drink.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] Users submitted entries such as "Diabeetus", "Fapple", several variations of "Gushing Granny", and "Hitler did nothing wrong".
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] On October 18, 2006, the Department of Homeland Security warned National Football League officials in Miami, New York City, Atlanta, Seattle, Houston, Oakland, and Cleveland about a possible threat involving the simultaneous use of dirty bombs at stadiums.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] The threat claimed that the attack would be carried out on October 22, the final day of the Muslim holy month of Ramadan.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] Both the FBI and the Department of Homeland Security expressed doubt concerning the credibility of the threats, but warned the relevant organizations as a precaution.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] The threat turned out to be an ill-conceived hoax perpetrated by a grocery store clerk in Wisconsin with no terrorist ties.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] The FBI considered it a clearly frivolous threat and the 20-year-old man was charged with fabricating a terrorist threat, sentenced to six months in prison followed by six months' house arrest, and ordered to pay $26,750 in restitution.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] Around midnight on September 11, 2007, a student posted photographs of mock pipe bombs and another photograph of him holding them while saying he would blow up his high school—Pflugerville High School in Pflugerville, Texas—at 9:11 am on September 11.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] Users of 4chan helped to track him down by finding the perpetrator's father's name in the Exif data of a photograph he took, and contacted the police.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] He was arrested before school began that day.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] The incident turned out to be a hoax; the "weapons" were toys and there were no actual bombs.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] A 20-year-old from Melbourne, Australia, was arrested on December 8, 2007, after apparently posting on 4chan that he was "going to shoot and kill as many people as I can until which time I am incapacitated or killed by the police".
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] The post, accompanied by an image of another man holding a shotgun, threatened a shopping mall near Beverly Hills.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] While the investigation was still open, he was charged with criminal defamation for a separate incident but died before the case was heard.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] On February 4, 2009, a posting on the 4chan /b/ board said there would be a school shooting at St Eskils Gymnasium in Eskilstuna, Sweden, leading 1,250 students and 50 teachers to be evacuated.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] A 21-year-old man was arrested after 4chan provided the police with the IP address of the poster.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] Police said that the suspect called it off as a joke, and they released him after they found no indication that the threat was serious.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] On June 28, 2018, a man was arrested following an indictment by the U.S.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] "I'm going to bring a Remington 700 and start shooting Alt-right guys.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] We need sympathy after that landwhale got all the liberals teary-eyed, so someone is going to have to make it look like the left is becoming more violent and radicalized.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] It's a false flag for sure, but I'll be aiming for the more tanned/dark-haired muddied jeans in the crowd so real whites won't have to worry," he wrote, according to the indictment.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] In 2023, a 38-year-old of Monmouth Junction, New Jersey was arrested for threatening Volusia County, Florida, Sheriff Mike Chitwood on 4chan due to Chitwood's condemnation of antisemitism.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] According to authorities, the poster, who lived 974 miles away from Volusia County, advocated "shoot[ing] Chitwood in the head and murder[ing] him" in a February 22 post.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] In April of that same year, two other 4chan users, residents of California and Connecticut respectively, were also arrested for threatening to kill Chitwood on 4chan.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] On the evening of April 2 and morning of April 3, 2024, two threats were posted on 4chan claiming there was a bomb in the Norwegian parliament building.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] Oslo police closed down the parliament building while the Norwegian Police Security Service carried out an investigation.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] The culprit behind the threats was not identified and nobody was arrested in relation to the case.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] On August 31, 2014, a compromise of user passwords at iCloud allowed a large number of private photographs taken by celebrities to be posted online, initially on 4chan.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] As a result of the incident, 4chan announced that it would enforce a Digital Millennium Copyright Act policy, which would allow content owners to remove material that had been shared on the site illegally, and would ban users who repeatedly posted stolen material.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] Also in August 2014, 4chan was involved in the Gamergate controversy, which began with unsubstantiated allegations about indie game developer Zoë Quinn from an ex-boyfriend, followed by false allegations from anonymous Internet users.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] The allegations were followed by a harassment campaign against several women in the video game industry, organized by 4chan users, particularly /r9k/.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] Discussion regarding Gamergate was banned on 4chan due to alleged rule violations, and Gamergate supporters moved to alternate forums such as 8chan.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] According to court documents filed on November 5, 2014, there were images posted to 4chan that appeared to be of a murder victim.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] The body was discovered in Port Orchard, Washington, after the images were posted.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] The posts were accompanied by the text: "Turns out it's way harder to strangle someone to death than it looks on the movies." A later post said: "Check the news for Port Orchard, Washington, in a few hours.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] I just wanted to share the pics before they find me." The victim was Amber Lynn Coplin, aged 30.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] The suspect, 33-year-old David Michael Kalac, surrendered to police in Oregon later the same day; he was charged with second-degree murder involving domestic violence.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] Kalac was convicted in April 2017 and was sentenced to 82 years in prison the following month.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] A report of Jeffrey Epstein's death was posted on /pol/ around 40 minutes before ABC News broke the news.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] It was originally suspected that the unidentified person who made the posts may have been a first responder, prompting a review by the New York City Fire Department, who later stated that the post did not come from a member of its department.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] On May 14, 2022, a mass shooting occurred at a supermarket in Buffalo, New York, US.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] Gendron, is reported to have written a racist manifesto released May 12 (two days before the shooting), with the manifesto including birth date and other biographical details that match the suspect in custody.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] In the manifesto the author writes that in May 2020 he began to frequent 4chan, including its "Politically Incorrect" message board /pol/, where he was introduced to the Great Replacement conspiracy theory.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] On June 10, 2025, Ofcom, the British government's communications regulator, announced an investigation into 4chan for potential violations of the Online Safety Act 2023 (OSA), which took effect in the United Kingdom in April 2025.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] On August 13, 2025, Ofcom issued a provisional decision, finding that 4chan had contravened its duties under the OSA by failing to comply with two information requests from the regulator.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] 4chan's lawyer issued a statement that the website "will not pay any penalty".
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] He also stated, "American businesses do not surrender their First Amendment rights because a foreign bureaucrat sends them an email".
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] On August 27, 2025, 4chan along with Kiwi Farms filed a lawsuit against Ofcom in the United States.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] Ofcom initially responded, "We are aware of this lawsuit.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] On 19 March 2026, Ofcom issued 4chan a £450,000 fine for failing to implement age checks in line with the OSA.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] It also fined the site a further £20,000 for not specifying how users are protected from illegal content, and £50,000 for not carrying out an illegal content risk assessment.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] Ofcom set a deadline for 4chan to amend these breaches by April 2, after which they plan to impose daily fines for each breach of the OSA, totaling £900 per day.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] On July 26, 2009, AT&T's DSL branch temporarily blocked access to the img.4chan.org domain (host of /b/ and /r9k/), which was initially believed to be an attempt at Internet censorship, and met with hostility on 4chan's part.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] Major news outlets have reported that the issue may be related to the DDoS-ing of 4chan, and that 4chan users suspected the then-owner of Swedish-based website *Anontalk.com*.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] On February 4, 2010, 4chan started receiving reports from Verizon Wireless customers that they were having difficulties accessing the site's image boards.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] After investigating, Poole found out that only the traffic on port 80 to the *boards.4chan.org* domain was affected, leading members to believe that the block was intentional.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] Three days later, Verizon Wireless confirmed that 4chan was "explicitly blocked".
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] The block was lifted several days later.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] On March 20, 2019, Australian telecom company Telstra denied access to millions of Australians to 4chan, 8chan, Zero Hedge, and LiveLeak as a reaction to the Christchurch mosque shootings.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] Following the Christchurch mosque shootings, numerous ISPs temporarily blocked any site hosting a copy of the livestream of the shooting, including 4chan.
[src:fortran/4chan-p02] The ISPs included Spark, Vodafone, Vocus, and 2degrees.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The building is shaped like an irregular pentagon, with a chamfer cutting diagonally across what would typically be the southwest corner of a rectangular slab.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The facade is made of gray-green glass and polished granite, which Barnes intended would give the building the appearance of a prism.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The northeast corner of the tower is cantilevered over the main entrance, and there are no setbacks throughout the building's height.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Adjacent to 590 Madison Avenue's southwest corner is a privately owned public space covered by a glass structure, which contains chairs, tables, and bamboo trees.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] From 1938 to 1964, IBM was headquartered at one of the previous structures on the site.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Despite relocating its headquarters to a suburb of New York City, IBM retained office space at multiple locations in the city and proposed the current skyscraper to consolidate some of its operations.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] IBM owned the tower until May 1994, when it sold the building to Edward J.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Until the sale, IBM occupied most of the building's space; the firm continues to maintain offices in the building, though most space has been leased to other tenants.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The State Teachers Retirement System of Ohio, which became a co-owner in 1995 and eventually took over ownership of the whole building, sold it in 2025 to RXR Realty.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] 590 Madison Avenue is in the Midtown Manhattan neighborhood of New York City.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The rectangular land lot is bounded by Madison Avenue to the east, 57th Street to the north, and 56th Street to the south.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The land lot covers approximately 39,162 square feet (3,638.3 m2), with a frontage of 200 feet (61 m) on Madison Avenue and 195 feet (59 m) on both 56th and 57th Streets.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The building is on the same city block as Trump Tower and the Tiffany & Co. flagship store to the west.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] In 1936, the IBM Corporation acquired an existing 20-story building at 590 Madison Avenue, at the southwest corner of 57th Street.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The IBM headquarters opened within that building two years later.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] IBM acquired additional adjacent lots in 1973.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] At the time, a pair of buildings designed by Carrère and Hastings occupied part of the site.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] One of these buildings, at 14 East 57th Street, was designed for art gallery operator Roland Knoedler.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The current skyscraper's site was also occupied by an eight-story apartment studio at 12 East 57th Street.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] At the northwest corner of Madison Avenue and 56th Street was a 13-story structure.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] 590 Madison Avenue was originally owned by IBM and thus called the "IBM Building".
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] 590 Madison Avenue was designed by Edward Larrabee Barnes and Associates.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Avakian were the associates-in-charge while Richard Klibschon was the project architect.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Antanas Vytuvis was the chief resident architect.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] In addition, James Ruderman was the structural engineer, LeMessurier Associates was the structural consultant, and Joseph R.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Loring & Associates was the mechanical and electrical engineer.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Turner Construction was the general contractor.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The 41-story building is 603 feet (184 m) tall and contains a pentagonal floor plan.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Adjacent to the building on its southwest corner is an enclosed atrium, a privately owned public space covered by a glass structure.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] As of 2020, the State Teachers Retirement System of Ohio owns the entire building and holds the land under it.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] A portion of the land owned by STRS Ohio is leased to The Trump Organization.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The building was designed as a pentagonal wedge, with a large chamfer that cuts into the rectangular massing at the site's southwest corner.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] According to Barnes, this shape was chosen to highlight the presence of the public atrium, which otherwise would have been overlooked due to its relatively nondescript location in the middle of the block.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Barnes believed in the observance of an older New York City zoning law, with the low-rise section of a skyscraper on a narrow street and the high-rise section on a wider street.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] As Madison Avenue and 57th Street are both wider than 56th Street, the bulk of the building is angled toward the former two streets at the northeast corner of the site.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The tower runs along the lot line on 57th Street but is set back 10 feet (3.0 m) from Madison Avenue.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The sidewalk, between the curb and the building's exterior wall, is made of green-granite squares measuring 40 by 40 inches (1,000 by 1,000 mm).
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The presence of the atrium at the southwest corner of the lot, and the fact that the tower only occupies 40 percent of the site, allowed the rest of the building to rise without setbacks.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Structurally, 590 Madison Avenue is a pentagon, with columns closely clustered on three sides (the southern and western facades are relatively short).
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] At the time of the IBM Building's completion, many of its contemporaries were International Style designs that used rectangular shapes.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Originally, the building was conceived with widely spaced groups of columns, but wind-tunnel tests found that the arrangement lacked rigidity and would cause the building to sway.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The building was thus stiffened, with columns being spaced every 14 feet (4.3 m) and with strengthened spandrel beams.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The first three floors at the northeast corner of the building are also chamfered.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] This allows the tower to cantilever over the main entrance at Madison Avenue and 57th Street.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The truss above the entrance only supports the weight of about ten stories above it.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Most of the stories above the cantilever are instead supported by the other columns around the perimeter, which are strengthened at the base.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The cantilever reportedly added $10 million to the construction costs (equivalent to $26 million in 2024).
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The inclusion of the cantilever was in keeping with Barnes's tendency for "symbolic rather than purely structural expression", as author Eric Nash described it.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] 590 Madison Avenue contains a public atrium, originally known as the Garden Plaza.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] It was built under the terms of the 1961 Zoning Resolution, which allowed New York City developers a zoning "bonus" for including open space in front of their buildings, and its presence enabled the addition of 100,000 square feet (9,300 m2), the equivalent of five stories.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The atrium is within the chamfer created by cutting off the building's southwest corner.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] This atrium directly connects to Trump Tower's atrium, connecting west to Fifth Avenue.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Combined with the atrium at 550 Madison Avenue, the atrium also creates a continuous corridor between 55th and 57th Streets.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Originally, the atrium was meant to provide access to the adjacent Bonwit Teller department store building to the west.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] In a 2000 study of over five hundred privately owned public spaces across New York City, Jerold Kayden classified the building's atrium as one of fifteen that were "of such high quality that they draw visitors from around the city".
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Most of the atrium is enclosed by a sawtooth-shaped glass canopy rising 68 feet (21 m).
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The canopy itself is 16 feet (4.9 m) tall and consists of six ridges.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] There is an illuminated ceiling above the western part of the atrium, connecting the entrances on 56th and 57th Streets.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The atrium was designed to be temperature-controlled, with an air conditioning system cooling or heating the space if the temperature outdoors fell below 32 °F (0 °C) or above 95 °F (35 °C).
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] This keeps the atrium at a similar temperature to climates in Virginia or North Carolina, between 40 and 90 °F (4 and 32 °C).
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] To conserve energy, the windows were double-glazed and tinted.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The atrium was originally conceived as a space that was open to the outdoors, but wind tunnel testing showed that doors needed to be added at each end.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Zion and Breen were hired to landscape the atrium.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Some 300 North Carolina-sourced bamboo trees were arranged in eleven groves, illuminated by lighting from 2 to 7 a.m. each day.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The New York Botanical Garden was tasked with maintaining the atrium and operated a shop there.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] After a renovation in 1995, eight sculptures were installed in the atrium, which was rebranded "The Sculpture Garden at 590 Madison".
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Eight of the eleven bamboo groves were retained.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The atrium contains food and drink kiosks, tables, chairs, and receptacles, and it is also used to display artwork.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Below ground level, the atrium was designed with an exhibition space called the Gallery of Science and Art, covering 13,000 square feet (1,200 m2), though this space closed in 1993.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] At the southeast corner of the site, on the corner of Madison Avenue and 56th Street, is a steel-and-granite fountain entitled *Levitated Mass*.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The fountain was created by Michael Heizer and dedicated in 1982.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] It contains an 11-short-ton (9.8-long-ton; 10.0 t) boulder within a frame measuring 25 by 16 feet (7.6 by 4.9 m), surrounded by a ledge with pedestrian seating.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The boulder appears to float over running water.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] To create the fountain, Heizer sheared off the top of a large rock and cut grooves into the surface before setting it on supports hidden within a stainless steel structure.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Heizer said of the fountain's name: "I don't use Greek names as titles, or dedicate artworks to my friends.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] At the northeast corner of the site, underneath the cantilevered main entrance on the corner of Madison Avenue and 57th Street, is a bright red sculpture by Alexander Calder, entitled *Saurien.* Standing 18 feet (5.5 m) tall, it was completed in 1975.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The sculpture's name refers to the French spelling of the word "saurian", which in turn refers to a reptilian clade.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The sculpture was installed under the main entrance during a 1995 renovation.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The building's facade consists of horizontal strips of gray-green glass between spandrel panels of polished granite.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The gray-green facade was intended to blend in with the Corning Glass Building as well as 590 Madison Avenue's atrium.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] About 15,000 slabs of Canadian granite are used on the facade.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] American sculptor James Rappa was hired to select the granite from the LaCroix quarry in Saint-Sébastien, Estrie, Quebec, and classify it with three grades of quality.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Rappa discarded the lowest-quality granite and used the highest-quality material on the lower stories.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Barnes had specified the granite be polished because it would help make the building look like a prism.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] In total, the granite slabs cover around 270,000 square feet (25,000 m2).
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Each slab has surface dimensions of 3.5 by 5 feet (1.1 by 1.5 m) and is about 3 inches (76 mm) thick.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Eight slabs are mounted to a single truss to create a continuous panel generally measuring 7 by 20 feet (2.1 by 6.1 m).
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] At the building's chamfer and each corner, the panels are half as wide.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The panels measure 9.5 inches (240 mm) thick in total.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The 3-inch-thick granite slabs, at the front of each panel, are mounted to the truss using stainless-steel angles.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] In case rust developed on the trusses, the rust would not stain the granite.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The outside face of each truss, directly behind the granite slabs, contains ducts.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The backs of the panels consist of 2 inches (51 mm) of mineral insulation.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Each panel is attached to the building's superstructure at six locations.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The windows comprise 35 percent of the facade.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Each window is double-glazed and consists of a blue-green 0.25-inch (6.4 mm) outer pane and a clear 0.25-inch (6.4 mm) inner pane, separated by a gap of 0.5 inches (13 mm).
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The double-glazing allows 65 percent of light into the building.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Moisture protection for the window frames and granite spandrels was developed concurrently.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] In case the insulation sealant failed, rainwater could collect at the bottom of each spandrel, where it could flow down the facade's vertical mullions to the bottom of the window.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The rainwater could then drain to ground level through a notch used by the building's window cleaning equipment, preventing ice buildup and granite staining.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The building was designed with 38 floors of offices, an employee cafeteria story, two retail stories, and two mechanical stories.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] 590 Madison Avenue has 1,030,000 square feet (96,000 m2) of floor area and 24 elevators, according to its official specifications.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Eighteen of the elevators are for passengers while six are for freight.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The elevators are oriented on a diagonal axis in the lobby, being positioned within banks that run from southwest to northeast.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The lobby itself is a triple-height space, designed with a direct view of the atrium behind it.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Barnes had intended for the lobby to be a continuation of the exterior and, as such, the lobby's floor contains granite pavement.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Artworks are also displayed in the lobby.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Chermayeff and Geismar Associates were the graphics consultants and Donald Bliss was the lighting consultant.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] On the upper stories, offices are arranged around the core, though the arrangements are flexible.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The office stories have a minimum ceiling height of 9 feet (2.7 m) and some perimeter offices can have a ceiling height of at least 9.5 feet (2.9 m).
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] There is a 3,000-kilowatt (4,000 hp) diesel electricity generator that can provide energy to the building in case of power outages.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] IBM's headquarters had been at the previous structure at 590 Madison Avenue from 1938 to 1964, when it moved to Armonk, New York, a northern suburb of New York City.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] IBM kept offices at 590 Madison, but it had decided to move its administrative officials after a successful experiment with opening a suburban office.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The next year, it bought a plot at the northwest corner of Madison Avenue and 50th Street, next to the old headquarters.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Pei to draw preliminary plans for a skyscraper replacing its old Madison Avenue headquarters.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The company rejected Pei's plans for unknown reasons.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] IBM acquired several other adjacent buildings and unsuccessfully attempted to acquire the air rights over the Tiffany & Co. flagship store and the Bonwit Teller store to the west.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] In 1973, IBM completed the acquisition of plots adjacent to its old 590 Madison Avenue headquarters.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] This gave the company a plot of 54,000 square feet (5,000 m2), of which 40 percent could be used for the development of a skyscraper with up to 45 floors and 972,000 square feet (90,300 m2).
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Barnes had been hired to make "preliminary plans" for the skyscraper.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] During the early design stages, IBM ran computer models to determine how to minimize the building's energy usage.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] By December 1976, Barnes had developed plans for a five-sided skyscraper with 830,000 square feet (77,000 m2) of space across 38 stories.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The building would allow IBM to consolidate many of its offices across the city, which at the time comprised 1.5 million square feet (140,000 m2) at 23 locations.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] IBM already occupied most of the space in the six existing structures on the site.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] To accommodate its operations, IBM had to lease space at several other buildings across the New York metropolitan area.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The skyscraper would be able to fit eight of IBM's twelve Manhattan offices and would also contain exhibition space at the rear.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Barnes contemplated whether to make the facade out of granite, glass, aluminum, or steel.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Barnes decided to use gray-green granite, so his design team traveled to several quarries across the world, including in Canada, Norway, Czechoslovakia, and Africa.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Ultimately, Barnes chose a sample of consistently mottled Canadian granite quarried in Quebec, eschewing a sample quarried from upstate New York with a more random pattern.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The original building was demolished starting in 1977.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] A *New York Times* editorial in January 1978 praised the IBM project, as well as the AT&T Building being constructed simultaneously at 550 Madison Avenue, as a "declaration of corporate commitment" to New York City, which had then recently rebounded from its fiscal crisis.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Plans for the building had been changed by July 1978, when the site had been cleared.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Work was about to proceed on the skyscraper, which had been revised to 43 stories (including the concourse and mezzanine at the building's base).
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] John Burgee, architect of the neighboring AT&T Building, said at the time that he had designed the AT&T project with a pink facade to complement the planned IBM Building's gray-green facade.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The Associated Press described the IBM Building as an extension of a "building boom" in the city that also included the AT&T Building and the Grand Hyatt New York.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Turner Construction was selected the same month as the construction contractor.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Because the IBM and AT&T buildings were simultaneously under construction on 56th Street, access to that street was limited.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] As a result, trucks delivering materials for both buildings would be backed up for several blocks along Madison Avenue.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The first of the building's granite facade slabs was delivered in early 1981.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] After being quarried in Quebec, the granite was sent to Hohmann & Barnard's facility in Hauppauge, New York, on Long Island.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Hohmann & Bernard carved the granite into slabs, and ten truckloads of four slabs each were sent to the worksite every week.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] At the construction site, the panels were assembled and a sealant was applied.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] By 1982, the atrium was being furnished.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The IBM Building was dedicated on October 4, 1983.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The first exhibition in the building's public gallery, "Innovation in IBM Computer Technology", opened that month, showing devices made by the company over the previous five decades.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] From the outset, IBM owned 590 Madison Avenue and occupied all of the space within the building.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Jerold Kayden wrote that the building's public atrium became "New York City's peerless privately owned public space".
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Initially, the bamboo plants in the IBM atrium were not well maintained, as the bamboo plants died within six months of being planted.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] To solve this issue, horticulturalists rotated the plants every six months, which IBM supported up until the company's budget tightened.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Economic troubles in the early 1990s forced IBM to downsize some of its real estate holdings.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] By 1993, IBM no longer occupied much of 590 Madison Avenue and was offering it under subleases to other companies.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] That March, IBM announced it would close the Gallery of Science and Art in the lower atrium to save money, despite the fact that the gallery saw 500 to 750 thousand visitors every year.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The following year, IBM indicated it would lease out as much as half of the building's office space.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] In May 1994, IBM sold the building to a joint venture of Edward J.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Minskoff and Odyssey Partners for an estimated $200 million.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The other two-thirds of the building remained unleased because of IBM's reduced occupancy requirements, However, with a recovering market for office space, real estate executives quoted in *The New York Times* said that Minskoff and Odyssey would not have a difficult time leasing the space.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Rumors circulated that IBM would relocate its headquarters back to Manhattan from Armonk, though IBM denied the reports.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The following year, the State Teachers Retirement System of Ohio, a pension fund, was brought on as a partner.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The pension fund received a five-year floating-rate mortgage from the Morgan Guaranty Trust Company.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] By 1995, the atrium had become dingy and there were complaints that homeless people were loitering in the atrium.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] That year, Minskoff proposed modifying the atrium; since it could affect the building's development bonus, the New York City Planning Commission had to review and approve the proposal.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Minskoff planned to use forty percent of the atrium space for exhibiting sculptures and remove many trees, tables, and chairs.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Critics objected that the public character of the atrium would be altered.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The commission ultimately approved a modified plan for the atrium renovation that October.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Other disputes over the atrium involved disagreements over whether the atrium should be closed during the daytime.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Part of the former Gallery of Science and Art space was taken in 1995 by the Freedom Forum organization, which stayed there until 2001.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Watch retailer Tourneau used another portion of the former gallery starting in 1996.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] A little more than a year after Minskoff and Odyssey bought the building, only seven floors were still unoccupied.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] This was in part due to a slight decline in office rents.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] STRS Ohio bought the remaining ownership stake in the property in 1997.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The building was worth $500 million by 1998, a 150 percent increase over what Minskoff and Odyssey had paid for it four years prior.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Odyssey wished to sell the building and hired Eastdil Realty to determine the value of its stake, but Minskoff said he would not sell his stake.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The Dahesh Museum of Art relocated into 590 Madison Avenue's exhibition space in 2003.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] STRS Ohio received a $350 million senior mortgage for the building in 2007 from Goldman Sachs.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The following year, the mozzarella bar Obika opened within the atrium, and Bonhams took some of the former IBM gallery space.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] In 2014, STRS Ohio considered selling a 49 percent minority ownership stake in 590 Madison Avenue.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The Safra family of Brazil were reportedly interested in taking the minority ownership stake; the family's offer would value the building at over $1.5 billion.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] STRS Ohio instead opted to refinance the building in 2015 with a ten-year, fixed-rate senior mortgage of $650 million, provided by Goldman Sachs.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Moed de Armas and Shannon conducted a renovation of the building, which was completed in 2016.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The lobby was refurbished and the elevator cabs were replaced as part of the project.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] STRS Ohio placed the building for sale in mid-2018, seeking up to $1.3 billion.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] At the time, IBM still occupied 120,000 square feet (11,000 m2) within the building.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] IBM announced in 2022 that it would be moving its offices to One Madison Avenue, while other space was leased to financial tenants.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] By 2024, further tenants had downsized their space in the building, which at the time was 77% occupied, a similar occupancy rate to other buildings nearby.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] At the time, STRS Ohio was contemplating further renovations at 590 Madison Avenue.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] In February 2025, STRS Ohio placed the building for sale with an asking price of $1.1 billion; several developers such as Blackstone Inc., RXR Realty, RFR Holding, SL Green Realty, and Tishman Speyer bid for the structure.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] RXR Realty won the right to buy the building for $1.1 billion in May 2025, making a down payment the next month.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] RXR's equity partner on the deal is Elliott Investment Management, the hedge fund founded by Paul Singer.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The purchase was finalized in August, making it the costliest sale of a New York City office building in seven years, and Apollo Global Management provided a $785 million loan to fund the purchase.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] As of 2020, almost half of the building's space was leased by the top ten tenants.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] IBM was the largest tenant with 11 percent of the space.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Before construction commenced, *New York Times* architecture writer Paul Goldberger said in July 1978, "IBM promises to be a dignified addition to midtown Manhattan", despite his feeling that the design was "conservative indeed".
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] As construction proceeded, Goldberger remained ambivalent about the tower, saying that the pentagonal shape and cantilevered entrance were "dramatic gestures" but that the facade looked too much like stone.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Der Scutt, architect of the neighboring Trump Tower, said in 1981 in response to criticism of 550 and 590 Madison Avenue: "I can't find anything oppressively hideous in IBM or AT&T.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Goldberger was greatly disappointed when the building was completed, writing in 1983 that the design has "generally fallen short of expectations", particularly in its atrium, entrance, and facade.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] He strongly preferred the design of 535 Madison Avenue three blocks south, also designed by Barnes.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Architectural critic Brendan Gill likewise said of IBM: "Their idea of social awareness was to include a museum and an atrium lobby.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] They forgot that the building destroys the scale of the area." Martin Filler also disliked the design of the facade and atrium, though he praised Heizer's fountain as "superb".
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] After the renovation of the atrium, Goldberger still disapproved of its design, saying that the "Zen"-like quality of the original atrium "is now compromised".
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Stern wrote that the IBM Building "was a challenge to the prevailing Modernist taste for glass, but it lacked the iconoclastic panache" of Philip Johnson's pink-granite design of 550 Madison Avenue.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] *Architectural Record* said in 1984: "The IBM Building may share with [the Seagram Building] the honor of being one of the two best Modern Movement skyscrapers yet built".
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Some critics also regarded the atrium highly.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Anthony Paletta of *The Daily Beast* said in 2022 that 590 Madison Avenue "features a very appealing atrium" in addition to the lobby's large collection of art.
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] Architectural critic Donald Martin Reynolds said the atrium and street "are ingeniously combined so that there is no loss of space, each one flowing into the other".
[src:fortran/590-madison-avenue] The book *Privately Owned Public Space* describes the atrium as "A tree-filled conservatory and public living room rolled into one".
[src:fortran/a-0-system] The **A-0 system** (*Arithmetic Language version 0*) was an early compiler-related tool developed for electronic computers, written by Grace Murray Hopper in 1951 and 1952 originally for the UNIVAC I.
[src:fortran/a-0-system] The A-0 functioned more as a loader or linker than the modern notion of a compiler.
[src:fortran/a-0-system] A program was specified as a sequence of subroutines and its arguments.
[src:fortran/a-0-system] The subroutines were identified by a numeric code and the arguments to the subroutines were written directly after each subroutine code.
[src:fortran/a-0-system] The A-0 system converted the specification into machine code that could be fed into the computer a second time to execute the said program.
[src:fortran/a-0-system] The A-0 system was followed by the A-1, A-2, A-3 (released as ARITH-MATIC), AT-3 (released as MATH-MATIC), and B-0 (released as FLOW-MATIC).
[src:fortran/a-0-system] The A-2 system was developed at the UNIVAC division of Remington Rand in 1953 and released to customers by the end of that year.
[src:fortran/a-0-system] Customers were provided the source code for A-2 and invited to send their improvements back to UNIVAC.
[src:fortran/a-0-system] Thus, A-2 could be considered an example of the result of an early philosophy similar to free and open-source software.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Fortran was originally developed by IBM with a reference manual being released in 1956; however, the first compilers only began to produce accurate code two years later.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Fortran computer programs have been written to support scientific and engineering applications, such as numerical weather prediction, finite element analysis, computational fluid dynamics, plasma physics, geophysics, computational physics, crystallography and computational chemistry.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] It is a popular language for high-performance computing and is used for programs that benchmark and rank the world's fastest supercomputers.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Fortran has evolved through numerous versions and dialects.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The two most important early versions were FORTRAN II and FORTRAN IV.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] In 1966, the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) developed a standard for Fortran to limit proliferation of compilers using slightly different syntax.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Successive versions have added support for a character data type, structured programming (Fortran 77), array programming, modular programming, generic programming (Fortran 90), parallel computing (Fortran 95), object-oriented programming (Fortran 2003), and concurrent programming (Fortran 2008).
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The first manual for FORTRAN describes it as a *Formula Translating System*, and printed the name with small caps, Fortran.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Other sources suggest the name stands for *Formula Translator*, or, most commonly, *Formula Translation*.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Early IBM computers did not support lowercase letters, and the names of versions of the language through FORTRAN 77 were usually spelled in all-uppercase.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] FORTRAN 77 was the last version in which the Fortran character set included only uppercase letters.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The Fortran 90 standard changed the language name from "FORTRAN" with all-caps to "Fortran" with initial caps.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Backus submitted a proposal to his superiors at IBM to develop a more practical alternative to assembly language for programming their IBM 704 mainframe computer.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Backus' historic FORTRAN team consisted of programmers Richard Goldberg, Sheldon F.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Best, Harlan Herrick, Peter Sheridan, Roy Nutt, Robert Nelson, Irving Ziller, Harold Stern, Lois Haibt, and David Sayre.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Its concepts included easier entry of equations into a computer, an idea developed by J.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Halcombe Laning and demonstrated in the Laning and Zierler system of 1952.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] A draft specification for *The IBM Mathematical Formula Translating System* was completed by November 1954.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The first manual for FORTRAN appeared in October 1956, with the first FORTRAN compiler delivered in April 1957.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Fortran produced efficient enough code for assembly language programmers to accept a high-level programming language replacement.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] John Backus said during a 1979 interview with *Think*, the IBM employee magazine, "Much of my work has come from being lazy.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The language was widely adopted by scientists for writing numerically intensive programs, which encouraged compiler writers to produce compilers that could generate faster and more efficient code.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The inclusion of a complex number data type in the language made Fortran especially suited to technical applications such as electrical engineering.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] By 1960, versions of FORTRAN were available for the IBM 709, 650, 1620, and 7090 computers.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Significantly, the increasing popularity of FORTRAN spurred competing computer manufacturers to provide FORTRAN compilers for their machines, so that by 1963 over 40 FORTRAN compilers existed.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] So pervasive was the language within the computing industry that by that time, over 220,000 Fortran manuals of all kinds had been distributed.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] FORTRAN was provided for the IBM 1401 computer by an innovative 63-phase compiler that ran entirely in its core memory of only 8000 (six-bit) characters.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The compiler could be run from tape, or from a 2200-card deck; it used no further tape or disk storage.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] It kept the program in memory and loaded overlays that gradually transformed it, in place, into executable form, as described by Haines.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] This article was reprinted, edited, in both editions of *Anatomy of a Compiler* and in the IBM manual "Fortran Specifications and Operating Procedures, IBM 1401".
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The executable form was not entirely machine language; rather, floating-point arithmetic, sub-scripting, input/output, and function references were interpreted, preceding UCSD Pascal P-code by two decades.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] GOTRAN, a simplified, interpreted version of FORTRAN I (with only 12 types of statements not 32) for "load and go" operation was available (at least for the early IBM 1620 computer).
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Modern Fortran, and almost all later versions, are fully compiled, as done for other high-performance languages.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The development of Fortran paralleled the early evolution of compiler technology, and many advances in the theory and design of compilers were specifically motivated by the need to generate efficient code for Fortran programs.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Indeed, the Fortran compiler was one of the most complicated programs of any kind in existence at the time, and it was used by IBM's Product Test group in Poughkeepsie, New York, as part of acceptance testing for newly built computers.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The arithmetic `IF` statement was reminiscent of (but not readily implementable by) a three-way comparison instruction (CAS—Compare Accumulator with Storage) available on the 704.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The statement provided the only way to compare numbers—by testing their difference, with an attendant risk of overflow.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] This deficiency was later overcome by "logical" facilities introduced in FORTRAN IV.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The `FREQUENCY` statement was used originally (and optionally) to give branch probabilities for the three branch cases of the arithmetic `IF` statement.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] It could also be used to suggest how many iterations a `DO` loop might run.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The first FORTRAN compiler used this weighting to perform *at compile time* a Monte Carlo simulation of the generated code, the results of which were used to optimize the placement of basic blocks in memory—a very sophisticated optimization for its time.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The first FORTRAN compiler reported diagnostic information by halting the program when an error was found and outputting an error code on its console.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] That code could be looked up by the programmer in an error messages table in the operator's manual, providing them with a brief description of the problem.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Later, an error-handling subroutine to handle user errors such as division by zero, developed by NASA, was incorporated, informing users of which line of code contained the error.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Before the development of disk files, text editors and terminals, programs were most often entered on a keypunch keyboard onto 80-column punched cards, one line to a card.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The resulting deck of cards would be fed into a card reader to be compiled.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Punched card codes included no lower-case letters or many special characters, and special versions of the IBM 026 keypunch were offered that would correctly print the re-purposed special characters used in FORTRAN.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Reflecting punched card input practice, Fortran programs were originally written in a fixed-column format.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] A letter "C" in column 1 caused the entire card to be treated as a comment and ignored by the compiler.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Columns 73 to 80 could therefore be used for identification information, such as punching a sequence number or text, which could be used to re-order cards if a stack of cards was dropped; though in practice this was reserved for stable, production programs.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] An IBM 519 could be used to copy a program deck and add sequence numbers.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Some early compilers, e.g., the IBM 650's, had additional restrictions due to limitations on their card readers.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Keypunches could be programmed to tab to column 7 and skip out after column 72.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Later compilers relaxed most fixed-format restrictions, and the requirement was eliminated in the Fortran 90 standard.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Within the statement field, whitespace characters (blanks) were ignored outside a text literal.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] This allowed omitting spaces between tokens for brevity or including spaces within identifiers for clarity.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Note the slight visual difference between a comma and a period.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Hollerith strings, originally allowed only in FORMAT and DATA statements, were prefixed by a character count and the letter H (e.g., `26HTHIS IS ALPHANUMERIC DATA.`), allowing blanks to be retained within the character string.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The main enhancement was to support procedural programming by allowing user-written subroutines and functions which returned values with parameters passed by reference.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The COMMON statement provided a way for subroutines to access common (or global) variables.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Over the next few years, FORTRAN II added support for the `DOUBLE PRECISION` and `COMPLEX` data types.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Early FORTRAN compilers supported no recursion in subroutines.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The lack of recursion was a significant detriment to the language being used in conjunction with certain algorithms and applications, and indeed limited how programmers could think about such things.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Although not specified in FORTRAN 77, many F77 compilers supported recursion as an option, and the Burroughs mainframes, designed with recursion built-in, did so by default.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] It became a standard in Fortran 90 via the new keyword RECURSIVE.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] This program, for Heron's formula, reads data on a tape reel containing three 5-digit integers A, B, and C as input.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] There are no "type" declarations available: variables whose name starts with I, J, K, L, M, or N are "fixed-point" (i.e. integers), otherwise floating-point.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Since integers are to be processed in this example, the names of the variables start with the letter "I".
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The name of a variable must start with a letter and can continue with both letters and digits, up to a limit of six characters in FORTRAN II.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] If A, B, and C cannot represent the sides of a triangle in plane geometry, then the program's execution will end with an error code of "STOP 1".
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] IBM also developed a *FORTRAN III* in 1958 that allowed for inline assembly code among other features; however, this version was never released as a product.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Like the 704 FORTRAN and FORTRAN II, FORTRAN III included machine-dependent features that made code written in it unportable from machine to machine, as well as Boolean expression support.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Early versions of FORTRAN provided by other vendors suffered from the same disadvantage.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] IBM began development of **FORTRAN IV** in 1961 as a result of customer demands.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] FORTRAN IV was eventually released in 1962, first for the IBM 7030 ("Stretch") computer, followed by versions for the IBM 7090/7094 in 1963 and later for the IBM 1401 in 1966.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] By 1965, FORTRAN IV was supposed to be compliant with the *standard* being developed by the American Standards Association X3.4.3 FORTRAN Working Group.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Between 1966 and 1968, IBM offered several FORTRAN IV compilers for its System/360, each named by letters that indicated the minimum amount of memory the compiler needed to run.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] In particular, the FORTRAN H compiler played an important role in the development of certain kinds of optimization approaches, such as allocating a specific set of registers to hold the values of variables while in a loop.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Overall, the compiler had three levels of possible optimization, as Fortran compiler developers had learned early on that the ability to turn off optimization was a necessity, since it drove up compilation times considerability for program runs that often were not going to work anyway.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Even with the larger amount of main memory available to it, the FORTRAN H compiler was still organized via a number of overlays.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Overall, Fortran compilers were a significant source of revenue for IBM, with sales of some $300 million in 1966 (equivalent to $2,977 million in 2025).
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Digital Equipment Corporation maintained DECSYSTEM-10 Fortran IV (F40) for PDP-10 from 1967 to 1975.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Compilers were also available for the UNIVAC 1100 series and the Control Data 6000 series and 7000 series systems.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] In the FORTRAN IV programming environment of the era, except for that used on Control Data Corporation (CDC) systems, only one instruction was placed per line.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The CDC version allowed for multiple instructions per line if separated by a $ (dollar) character.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The FORTRAN sheet was divided into four fields, as described above.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Two compilers of the time, IBM "G" and UNIVAC, allowed comments to be written on the same line as instructions, separated by a special character: "master space": V (perforations 7 and 8) for UNIVAC and perforations 12/11/0/7/8/9 (hexadecimal FF) for IBM.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] These comments were not to be inserted in the middle of continuation cards.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The resulting two standards, approved in March 1966, defined two languages, *FORTRAN* (based on FORTRAN IV, which had served as a de facto standard), and *Basic FORTRAN* (based on FORTRAN II, but stripped of its machine-dependent features).
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The FORTRAN defined by the first standard, officially denoted X3.9-1966, became known as *FORTRAN 66* (although many continued to term it FORTRAN IV, the language on which the standard was largely based).
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] FORTRAN 66 effectively became the first industry-standard version of FORTRAN.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The above Fortran II version of the Heron program needs several modifications to compile as a Fortran 66 program.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Modifications include using the more machine independent versions of the `READ` and `WRITE` statements, and removal of the unneeded `FLOATF` type conversion functions.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Though not required, the arithmetic `IF` statements can be re-written to use logical `IF` statements and expressions in a more structured fashion.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Although ill-suited for most military-related applications, Fortran was nonetheless one of only a few high-level languages approved for use by the U.S.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Final drafts of this revised standard circulated in 1977, leading to formal approval of the new FORTRAN standard in April 1978.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] In this revision of the standard, a number of features were removed or altered in a manner that might invalidate formerly standard-conforming programs.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] A Fortran 77 version of the Heron program requires no modifications to the Fortran 66 version.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] However this example demonstrates additional cleanup of the I/O statements, including using list-directed I/O, and replacing the Hollerith edit descriptors in the `FORMAT` statements with quoted strings.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] It also uses structured `IF` and `END IF` statements, rather than `GOTO`/`CONTINUE`.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The development of a revised standard to succeed FORTRAN 77 would be repeatedly delayed as the standardization process struggled to keep up with rapid changes in computing and programming practice.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] In the meantime, as the "Standard FORTRAN" for nearly fifteen years, FORTRAN 77 would become the historically most important dialect.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] An important practical extension to FORTRAN 77 was the release of MIL-STD-1753 in 1978.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] This specification, developed by the U.S.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Department of Defense, standardized a number of features implemented by most FORTRAN 77 compilers but not included in the ANSI FORTRAN 77 standard.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] These features would eventually be incorporated into the Fortran 90 standard.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The IEEE 1003.9 POSIX Standard, released in 1991, provided a simple means for FORTRAN 77 programmers to issue POSIX system calls.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Over 100 calls were defined in the document – allowing access to POSIX-compatible process control, signal handling, file system control, device control, procedure pointing, and stream I/O in a portable manner.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The much-delayed successor to FORTRAN 77, informally known as *Fortran 90* (and prior to that, *Fortran 8X*), was finally released as ISO/IEC standard 1539:1991 in 1991 and an ANSI Standard in 1992.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Unlike the prior revision, Fortran 90 removed no features.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Any standard-conforming FORTRAN 77 program was also standard-conforming under Fortran 90, and either standard should have been usable to define its behavior.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] A small set of features were identified as "obsolescent" and were expected to be removed in a future standard.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] All of the functionalities of these early-version features can be performed by newer Fortran features.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Some are kept to simplify porting of old programs but many were deleted in Fortran 95.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] A number of intrinsic functions were extended (for example a `dim` argument was added to the `maxloc` intrinsic).
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] An important supplement to Fortran 95 was the ISO technical report *TR-15581: Enhanced Data Type Facilities*, informally known as the *Allocatable TR.* This specification defined enhanced use of `ALLOCATABLE` arrays, prior to the availability of fully Fortran 2003-compliant Fortran compilers.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Such uses include `ALLOCATABLE` arrays as derived type components, in procedure dummy argument lists, and as function return values.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] (`ALLOCATABLE` arrays are preferable to `POINTER`-based arrays because `ALLOCATABLE` arrays are guaranteed by Fortran 95 to be deallocated automatically when they go out of scope, eliminating the possibility of memory leakage.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Another important supplement to Fortran 95 was the ISO technical report *TR-15580: Floating-point exception handling*, informally known as the *IEEE TR.* This specification defined support for IEEE floating-point arithmetic and floating-point exception handling.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] which, together, compose the multi-part International Standard (ISO/IEC 1539).
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The language defined by the twenty-first century standards, in particular because of its incorporation of object-oriented programming support and subsequently Coarray Fortran, is often referred to as 'Modern Fortran', and the term is increasingly used in the literature.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] An important supplement to Fortran 2003 was the ISO technical report *TR-19767: Enhanced module facilities in Fortran.* This report provided *sub-modules,* which make Fortran modules more similar to Modula-2 modules.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] They are similar to Ada private child sub-units.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] This allows the specification and implementation of a module to be expressed in separate program units, which improves packaging of large libraries, allows preservation of trade secrets while publishing definitive interfaces, and prevents compilation cascades.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] ISO/IEC 1539-1:2010, informally known as Fortran 2008, was approved in September 2010.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] As with Fortran 95, this is a minor upgrade, incorporating clarifications and corrections to Fortran 2003, as well as introducing some new capabilities.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The Final Draft international Standard (FDIS) is available as document N1830.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] A supplement to Fortran 2008 is the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) Technical Specification (TS) 29113 on *Further Interoperability of Fortran with C*, which has been submitted to ISO in May 2012 for approval.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The specification adds support for accessing the array descriptor from C and allows ignoring the type and rank of arguments.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The Fortran 2018 revision of the language was earlier referred to as Fortran 2015.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] It was a significant revision and was released on November 28, 2018.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Additional changes and new features include support for ISO/IEC/IEEE 60559:2011 (the version of the IEEE floating-point standard before the latest minor revision IEEE 754–2019), hexadecimal input/output, IMPLICIT NONE enhancements and other changes.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Fortran 2018 deleted the arithmetic IF statement.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] It also deleted non-block DO constructs - loops which do not end with an END DO or CONTINUE statement.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] These had been an obsolescent part of the language since Fortran 90.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] New obsolescences are: COMMON and EQUIVALENCE statements and the BLOCK DATA program unit, labelled DO loops, specific names for intrinsic functions, and the FORALL statement and construct.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Fortran 2023 (ISO/IEC 1539-1:2023) was published in November 2023, and can be purchased from the ISO.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Fortran 2023 is a minor extension of Fortran 2018 that focuses on correcting errors and omissions in Fortran 2018.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] It also adds several small features, including conditional expressions and arguments, simple procedures, and an enumerated type capability.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Degree- and half revolution based trig functions were also added.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Degree-based trig functions were previously a very common vendor extension.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] A full description of the Fortran language features brought by Fortran 95 is covered in the related article, *Fortran 95 language features*.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The language versions defined by later standards are often referred to collectively as 'Modern Fortran' and are described in the literature.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Although a 1968 journal article by the authors of BASIC already described FORTRAN as "old-fashioned", programs have been written in Fortran for many decades and there is a vast body of Fortran software in daily use throughout the scientific and engineering communities.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Jay Pasachoff wrote in 1984 that "physics and astronomy students simply have to learn FORTRAN.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] So much exists in FORTRAN that it seems unlikely that scientists will change to Pascal, Modula-2, or whatever." In 1993, Cecil E.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Leith called FORTRAN the "mother tongue of scientific computing", adding that its replacement by any other possible language "may remain a forlorn hope".
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Many of the floating-point benchmarks to gauge the performance of new computer processors, such as the floating-point components of the SPEC benchmarks (e.g., CFP2006, CFP2017) are written in Fortran.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Math algorithms are well documented in Numerical Recipes.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Apart from this, more modern codes in computational science generally use large program libraries, such as METIS for graph partitioning, PETSc or Trilinos for linear algebra capabilities, deal.II or FEniCS for mesh and finite element support, and other generic libraries.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Since the early 2000s, many of the widely used support libraries have also been implemented in C and more recently, in C++.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] On the other hand, high-level languages such as the Wolfram Language, MATLAB, Python, and R have become popular in particular areas of computational science.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Consequently, a growing fraction of scientific programs are also written in such higher-level scripting languages.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] For this reason, facilities for inter-operation with C were added to Fortran 2003 and enhanced by the ISO/IEC technical specification 29113, which was incorporated into Fortran 2018 to allow more flexible interoperation with other programming languages.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Portability was a problem in the early days because there was no agreed upon standard—not even IBM's reference manual—and computer companies vied to differentiate their offerings from others by providing incompatible features.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The 1966 standard provided a reference syntax and semantics, but vendors continued to provide incompatible extensions.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Government were required to diagnose extensions of the standard.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Rather than offer two processors, essentially every compiler eventually had at least an option to diagnose extensions.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Incompatible extensions were not the only portability problem.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] For numerical calculations, it is important to take account of the characteristics of the arithmetic.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] This was addressed by Fox et al. in the context of the 1966 standard by the *PORT* library.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The ideas therein became widely used, and were eventually incorporated into the 1990 standard by way of intrinsic inquiry functions.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] The widespread (now almost universal) adoption of the IEEE 754 standard for binary floating-point arithmetic has essentially removed this problem.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Access to the computing environment (e.g., the program's command line, environment variables, textual explanation of error conditions) remained a problem until it was addressed by the 2003 standard.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] Large collections of library software that could be described as being loosely related to engineering and scientific calculations, such as graphics libraries, have been written in C, and therefore access to them presented a portability problem.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] This has been addressed by incorporation of C interoperability into the 2003 standard.
[src:fortran/fortran-p01] It is now possible (and relatively easy) to write an entirely portable program in Fortran, even without recourse to a preprocessor.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] Until the Fortran 66 standard was developed, each compiler supported its own variant of Fortran.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] Some were more divergent from the mainstream than others.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] One of the most prominent textbooks of the time, Daniel D.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] McCracken's *A Guide to FORTRAN IV Programming* (1965), devoted a full two-page matrix of 24 feature differences versus 29 manufacturer-and-computer versions.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] Another textbook author from that era, John M.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] Univac also offered a compiler for the 1100 series known as FORTRAN V.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] A spinoff of Univac Fortran V was Athena FORTRAN.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] For example, one of IBM's FORTRAN compilers (*H Extended IUP*) had a level of optimization which reordered the machine code instructions to keep multiple internal arithmetic units busy simultaneously.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] Another example is *CFD*, a special variant of FORTRAN designed specifically for the ILLIAC IV supercomputer, running at NASA's Ames Research Center.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] IBM Research Labs also developed an extended FORTRAN-based language called *VECTRAN* for processing vectors and matrices.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] Such machine-specific extensions have either disappeared over time or have had elements incorporated into the main standards.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] The major remaining extension is OpenMP, which is a cross-platform extension for shared memory programming.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] One new extension, Coarray Fortran, is intended to support parallel programming.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] Up to ten subroutines could be used in one program.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] FOR TRANSIT statements were limited to columns 7 through 56, only.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] Punched cards were used for input and output on the IBM 650.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] Two versions existed for the 650s with a 2000 word memory drum: FOR TRANSIT I (S) and FOR TRANSIT II, the latter for machines equipped with indexing registers and automatic floating-point decimal (bi-quinary) arithmetic.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] Appendix A of the manual included wiring diagrams for the IBM 533 card reader/punch control panel.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] The first FORTRAN compiler set a high standard of efficiency for compiled code.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] This goal made it difficult to create a compiler so it was usually done by the computer manufacturers to support hardware sales.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] The requirement for execution efficiency remained the primary design criteria for the language through the early evolution of the language.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] This left an important niche: compilers that were fast in the compilation and loading phase and provided good diagnostics for the programmer, who was often a student as by this time FORTRAN IV had started to become an important educational tool.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] WATFOR, introduced in the 1960s, was popularly used in colleges and universities.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] Developed, supported, and distributed by the University of Waterloo, WATFOR was based largely on FORTRAN IV.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] A student using WATFOR could submit their batch FORTRAN job and, if there were no syntax errors, the program would move straight to execution.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] This simplification allowed students to concentrate on their program's syntax and semantics, or execution logic flow, rather than dealing with submission Job Control Language (JCL), the compile/link-edit/execution successive process(es), or other complexities of a mainframe environment.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] Moreover, WATFOR presented a superset of the Fortran language, in particular providing so-called "free" `READ` and `PRINT` commands as an alternative to the formatted `READ` and `WRITE>` statements of regular Fortran.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] The `FORMAT` statements of the latter allowed considerable flexibility but could be quite complicated, and were sometimes subject to manufacturer differences or site-specific guidelines.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] Since the formatted approach caused even experienced programmers difficulties, providing an alternative in a student compiler was a definite advantage.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] A down side to this simplified environment was that WATFOR was not a good choice for programmers needing the expanded abilities of their host processor(s), e.g., WATFOR typically had very limited access to I/O devices.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] WATFOR was succeeded by WATFIV and later versions.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] Another student compiler was PUFFT, and on a smaller scale, FORGO, Wits Fortran, and Kingston Fortran 2.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] Prior to FORTRAN 77, many preprocessors were commonly used to provide a friendlier language, with the advantage that the preprocessed code could be compiled on any machine with a standard FORTRAN compiler.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] These preprocessors would typically support structured programming, variable names longer than six characters, additional data types, conditional compilation, and even macro capabilities.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] Popular preprocessors included EFL, FLECS, iftran, MORTRAN, SFtran, S-Fortran, Ratfor, and Ratfiv.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] EFL, Ratfor and Ratfiv, for example, implemented C-like languages, outputting preprocessed code in standard FORTRAN 66.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] The PFORT preprocessor was often used to verify that code conformed to a portable subset of the language.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] Despite advances in the Fortran language, preprocessors continue to be used for conditional compilation and macro substitution.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] LRLTRAN was developed at the Lawrence Radiation Laboratory to provide support for vector arithmetic and dynamic storage, among other extensions to support systems programming.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] The distribution included the Livermore Time Sharing System (LTSS) operating system.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] The Fortran-95 Standard includes an optional *Part 3* which defines an optional conditional compilation capability.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] This capability is often referred to as "CoCo".
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] Many Fortran compilers have integrated subsets of the C preprocessor into their systems.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] SIMSCRIPT is an application specific Fortran preprocessor for modeling and simulating large discrete systems.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] The F programming language was designed to be a clean subset of Fortran 95 that attempted to remove the redundant, unstructured, and deprecated features of Fortran, such as the `EQUIVALENCE` statement.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] F retains the array features added in Fortran 90, and removes control statements that were made obsolete by structured programming constructs added to both FORTRAN 77 and Fortran 90.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] F is described by its creators as "a compiled, structured, array programming language especially well suited to education and scientific computing".
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] Essential Lahey Fortran 90 (ELF90) was a similar subset.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] Lahey and Fujitsu teamed up to create Fortran for the Microsoft .NET Framework.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] Silverfrost FTN95 is also capable of creating .NET code.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] The following program demonstrates dynamic memory allocation and array-based operations, two features introduced with Fortran 90.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] Particularly noteworthy is the absence of `DO` loops and `IF`/`THEN` statements in manipulating the array; mathematical operations are applied to the array as a whole.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] Also apparent is the use of descriptive variable names and general code formatting that conform with contemporary programming style.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] This example computes an average over data entered interactively.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] During the same FORTRAN standards committee meeting at which the name "FORTRAN 77" was chosen, a satirical technical proposal was incorporated into the official distribution bearing the title "Letter O Considered Harmful".
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] This proposal purported to address the confusion that sometimes arises between the letter "O" and the numeral zero, by eliminating the letter from allowable variable names.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] However, the method proposed was to eliminate the letter from the character set entirely (thereby retaining 48 as the number of lexical characters, which the colon had increased to 49).
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] This was considered beneficial in that it would promote structured programming, by making it impossible to use the notorious `GO TO` statement as before.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] (Troublesome `FORMAT` statements would also be eliminated.) It was noted that this "might invalidate some existing programs" but that most of these "probably were non-conforming, anyway".
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] When X3J3 debated whether the minimum trip count for a DO loop should be zero or one in Fortran 77, Loren Meissner suggested a minimum trip count of two—reasoning *(tongue-in-cheek)* that if it were less than two, then there would be no reason for a loop.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] When assumed-length arrays were being added, there was a dispute as to the appropriate character to separate upper and lower bounds.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] In a comment examining these arguments, Walt Brainerd penned an article entitled "Astronomy vs.
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] Gastroenterology" because some proponents had suggested using the star or asterisk ("*"), while others favored the colon (":").
[src:fortran/fortran-p02] Variable names beginning with the letters I–N have a default type of integer, while variables starting with any other letters defaulted to real, although programmers could override the defaults with an explicit declaration.
[src:fortran/net-framework] The **.NET Framework** (pronounced "*dot net*") is a proprietary software framework developed by Microsoft that runs primarily on Microsoft Windows.
[src:fortran/net-framework] It was the predominant implementation of the Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) until being superseded by the cross-platform .NET project.
[src:fortran/net-framework] It includes a large class library called Framework Class Library (FCL) and provides language interoperability (each language can use code written in other languages) across several programming languages.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Programs written for .NET Framework execute in a software environment (in contrast to a hardware environment) named the Common Language Runtime (CLR).
[src:fortran/net-framework] The CLR is an application virtual machine that provides services such as security, memory management, and exception handling.
[src:fortran/net-framework] As such, computer code written using .NET Framework is called "managed code".
[src:fortran/net-framework] FCL and CLR together constitute the .NET Framework.
[src:fortran/net-framework] FCL provides the user interface, data access, database connectivity, cryptography, web application development, numeric algorithms, and network communications.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Programmers produce software by combining their source code with the .NET Framework and other libraries.
[src:fortran/net-framework] The framework is intended to be used by most new applications created for the Windows platform.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Microsoft also produces an integrated development environment for .NET software called Visual Studio.
[src:fortran/net-framework] .NET Framework began as proprietary software, although the firm worked to standardize the software stack almost immediately, even before its first release.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Despite the standardization efforts, developers, mainly those in the free and open-source software communities, expressed their unease with the selected terms and the prospects of any free and open-source implementation, especially regarding software patents.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Since then, Microsoft has changed .NET development to more closely follow a contemporary model of a community-developed software project, including issuing an update to its patent promising to address the concerns.
[src:fortran/net-framework] In April 2019, Microsoft released .NET Framework 4.8, the last major version of the framework as a proprietary offering, followed by .NET Framework 4.8.1 in August 2022.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Only monthly security and reliability bug fixes to that version have been released since then.
[src:fortran/net-framework] No further changes to that version are planned.
[src:fortran/net-framework] The .NET Framework will continue to be included with future releases of Windows and continue to receive security updates, with no plans to remove it as of July 2025.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Microsoft began developing .NET Framework in the late 1990s, originally under the name of Next Generation Windows Services (NGWS), as part of the Microsoft .NET strategy.
[src:fortran/net-framework] By early 2000, the first beta versions of .NET 1.0 were released.
[src:fortran/net-framework] In August 2000, Microsoft and Intel worked to standardize Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) and C#.
[src:fortran/net-framework] By December 2001, both were ratified as ECMA standards.
[src:fortran/net-framework] International Organization for Standardization (ISO) followed in April 2003.
[src:fortran/net-framework] The current version of ISO standards are ISO/IEC 23271:2012 and ISO/IEC 23270:2006.
[src:fortran/net-framework] While Microsoft and their partners hold patents for CLI and C#, ECMA and ISO require that all patents essential to implementation be made available under "reasonable and non-discriminatory terms".
[src:fortran/net-framework] The firms agreed to meet these terms, and to make the patents available royalty-free.
[src:fortran/net-framework] However, this did not apply to the part of the .NET Framework not covered by ECMA-ISO standards, which included Windows Forms, ADO.NET, and ASP.NET.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Patents that Microsoft holds in these areas may have deterred non-Microsoft implementations of the full framework.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Windows Vista is the first client version of Windows that integrated the .NET Framework.
[src:fortran/net-framework] On October 3, 2007, Microsoft announced that the source code for .NET Framework 3.5 libraries was to become available under the Microsoft Reference Source License (Ms-RSL).
[src:fortran/net-framework] The source code repository became available online on January 16, 2008, and included BCL, ASP.NET, ADO.NET, Windows Forms, WPF, and XML.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Scott Guthrie of Microsoft promised that LINQ, WCF, and WF libraries were being added.
[src:fortran/net-framework] The .NET Compact Framework and .NET Micro Framework variants of the .NET Framework provided support for other Microsoft platforms such as Windows Mobile, Windows CE and other resource-constrained embedded devices.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Silverlight provided support for web browsers via plug-ins.
[src:fortran/net-framework] In November 2014, Microsoft also produced an update to its patent grants, which further extends the scope beyond its prior pledges.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Prior projects like Mono existed in a legal gray area because Microsoft's earlier grants applied only to the technology in "covered specifications", including strictly the 4th editions each of ECMA-334 and ECMA-335.
[src:fortran/net-framework] The new patent promise, however, places no ceiling on the specification version, and even extends to any .NET runtime technologies documented on MSDN that have not been formally specified by the ECMA group, if a project chooses to implement them.
[src:fortran/net-framework] This allows Mono and other projects to maintain feature parity with modern .NET features that have been introduced since the 4th edition was published all without being at risk of patent litigation over the implementation of those features.
[src:fortran/net-framework] The new grant does maintain the restriction that any implementation must maintain minimum compliance with the mandatory parts of the CLI specification.
[src:fortran/net-framework] On March 31, 2016, Microsoft announced at Microsoft Build that they will completely relicense Mono under an MIT License even in scenarios where formerly a commercial license was needed.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Microsoft also supplemented its prior patent promise for Mono, stating that they will not assert any "applicable patents" against parties that are "using, selling, offering for sale, importing, or distributing Mono." It was announced that the Mono Project was contributed to the .NET Foundation.
[src:fortran/net-framework] These developments followed the acquisition of Xamarin, which began in February 2016 and was finished on March 18, 2016.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Microsoft's press release highlights that the cross-platform commitment now allows for a fully open-source, modern server-side .NET stack.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Microsoft released the source code for WPF, Windows Forms and WinUI on December 4, 2018.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) provides a language-neutral platform for application development and execution.
[src:fortran/net-framework] By implementing the core aspects of .NET Framework within the scope of CLI, these functions will not be tied to one language but will be available across the many languages supported by the framework.
[src:fortran/net-framework] .NET Framework includes the Common Language Runtime (CLR).
[src:fortran/net-framework] It serves as the execution engine of .NET Framework and offers many services such as memory management, type safety, exception handling, garbage collection, security and thread management.
[src:fortran/net-framework] All programs written for .NET Framework are executed by the CLR.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Programs written for .NET Framework are compiled into Common Intermediate Language code (CIL), as opposed to being directly compiled into machine code.
[src:fortran/net-framework] During execution, an architecture-specific just-in-time compiler (JIT) turns the CIL code into machine code.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Compiled CLI code is stored in CLI assemblies.
[src:fortran/net-framework] As mandated by the specification, assemblies are stored in Portable Executable (PE) file format, common on Windows platform for all *dynamic-link library* (DLL) and *executable* EXE files.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Each assembly consists of one or more files, one of which must contain a manifest bearing the metadata for the assembly.
[src:fortran/net-framework] The complete name of an assembly (not to be confused with the file name on disk) contains its simple text name, version number, culture, and public key token.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Assemblies are considered equivalent if they share the same complete name.
[src:fortran/net-framework] A private key can also be used by the creator of the assembly for strong naming.
[src:fortran/net-framework] The public key token determines the real-world identity of the assembly's signer.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Only those knowing their private key (of the double-key cryptography system) can sign assemblies that have the same strong name as a prior version assembly.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Strong naming is required to add assemblies to Global Assembly Cache.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Starting with Visual Studio 2015, .NET Native compilation technology allows for the compilation of .NET code of Universal Windows Platform apps directly to machine code rather than CIL code, but the app must be written in either C# or Visual Basic.NET.
[src:fortran/net-framework] .NET Framework includes an implementation of the CLI foundational Standard Libraries.
[src:fortran/net-framework] The .NET Framework Class Library (FCL) is organized in a hierarchy of namespaces.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Most of the built-in application programming interfaces (APIs) are part of either `System.*` or `Microsoft.*` namespaces.
[src:fortran/net-framework] These class libraries implement many common functions, such as file reading and writing, graphic rendering, database interaction, and XML document manipulation.
[src:fortran/net-framework] The class libraries are available for all CLI compliant languages.
[src:fortran/net-framework] The FCL implements the CLI Base Class Library (BCL) and other class libraries—some are specified by CLI and others are Microsoft specific.
[src:fortran/net-framework] BCL includes a small subset of the entire class library and is the core set of classes that serve as the basic API of CLR.
[src:fortran/net-framework] For .NET Framework most classes considered being part of BCL reside in `mscorlib.dll`, `System.dll` and `System.Core.dll`.
[src:fortran/net-framework] BCL classes are available in .NET Framework as well as in CLI's alternative implementations, including .NET Compact Framework, Microsoft Silverlight, .NET Core and Mono.
[src:fortran/net-framework] FCL refers to the entire class library that ships with .NET Framework.
[src:fortran/net-framework] It includes BCL, an expanded set of libraries, including Windows Forms, ASP.NET, and Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF), and also extensions to the base class libraries ADO.NET, Language Integrated Query (LINQ), Windows Communication Foundation (WCF), and Workflow Foundation (WF).
[src:fortran/net-framework] FCL is much larger in scope than standard libraries for languages like C++, and comparable in scope to standard libraries of Java.
[src:fortran/net-framework] With the introduction of alternative CLI's implementations (e.g., Silverlight), Microsoft introduced the concept of Portable Class Libraries (PCL) allowing a consuming library to run on more than one implementation.
[src:fortran/net-framework] With the further proliferation of implementations, the PCL approach failed to scale (PCLs are defined intersections of API surface between two or more implementations).
[src:fortran/net-framework] As the next evolutionary step of PCL, the .NET Standard Library was created retroactively based on the `System.Runtime.dll` based APIs found in UWP and Silverlight.
[src:fortran/net-framework] New CLI's implementations are encouraged to implement a version of the Standard Library allowing them to run existent third-party libraries with no need of creating new versions of them.
[src:fortran/net-framework] The .NET Standard Library allows an independent evolution of the library and app model layers within the .NET architecture.
[src:fortran/net-framework] NuGet is the package manager for all .NET platforms.
[src:fortran/net-framework] It is used to retrieve third-party libraries into a .NET project with a global library feed at NuGet.org.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Private feeds can be maintained separately, e.g., by a build server or a file system directory.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Microsoft introduced C++/CLI in Visual Studio 2005, which is a language and means of compiling Visual C++ programs to run within the .NET Framework.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Some parts of the C++ program still run within an unmanaged Visual C++ Runtime, while specially modified parts are translated into CIL code and run with the .NET Framework's CLR.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Assemblies compiled using the C++/CLI compiler are termed mixed-mode assemblies since they contain native and managed code in the same DLL.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Such assemblies are more complex to reverse engineer since .NET decompilers such as .NET Reflector reveal only the managed code.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Because computer systems commonly require interaction between newer and older applications, .NET Framework provides means to access functions implemented in newer and older programs that execute outside .NET environment.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Access to Component Object Model (COM) components is provided in `System.Runtime.InteropServices` and `System.EnterpriseServices` namespaces of the framework.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Access to other functions is via Platform Invocation Services (P/Invoke).
[src:fortran/net-framework] Access to .NET functions from native applications is via the reverse P/Invoke function.
[src:fortran/net-framework] .NET Framework introduces a Common Type System (CTS) that defines all possible data types and programming constructs supported by CLR and how they may or may not interact conforming to CLI specifications.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Because of this feature, .NET Framework supports the exchange of types and object instances between libraries and applications written using any conforming CLI language.
[src:fortran/net-framework] CTS and the CLR used in .NET Framework also enforce type safety.
[src:fortran/net-framework] This prevents ill-defined casts, wrong method invocations, and memory size issues when accessing an object.
[src:fortran/net-framework] This also makes most CLI languages statically typed (with or without type inference).
[src:fortran/net-framework] However, starting with .NET Framework 4.0, the Dynamic Language Runtime extended the CLR, allowing dynamically typed languages to be implemented atop the CLI.
[src:fortran/net-framework] While Microsoft has never implemented the full framework on any system except Microsoft Windows, it has engineered the framework to be cross-platform, and implementations are available for other operating systems (see Silverlight and § Alternative implementations).
[src:fortran/net-framework] Microsoft submitted the specifications for CLI (which includes the Base Class Libraries, CTS, and CIL), C#, and C++/CLI to both Ecma International (ECMA) and International Organization for Standardization (ISO), making them available as official standards.
[src:fortran/net-framework] This makes it possible for third parties to create compatible implementations of the framework and its languages on other platforms.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Core cross-platform .NET (formerly .NET Core) is officially available also for many Linux distributions and macOS.
[src:fortran/net-framework] .NET Framework has its own security mechanism with two general features: Code Access Security (CAS), and validation and verification.
[src:fortran/net-framework] CAS is based on evidence that is associated with a specific assembly.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Typically, the evidence is the source of the assembly (whether it is installed on the local machine or has been downloaded from the Internet).
[src:fortran/net-framework] CAS uses evidence to determine the permissions granted to the code.
[src:fortran/net-framework] When calling code demands that it be granted a specific permission, CLR performs a call stack walk checking every assembly of each method in the call stack for the required permission; if any assembly is not granted the permission, it will throw a security exception.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Managed CIL bytecode is easier to reverse-engineer than native code, unless obfuscated. .NET decompiler programs enable developers with no reverse-engineering skills to view the source code behind unobfuscated .NET assemblies.
[src:fortran/net-framework] In contrast, apps compiled from native machine code are much harder to reverse-engineer, and source code is almost never produced successfully, mainly because of compiler optimizations and lack of reflection.
[src:fortran/net-framework] This creates concerns in the business community over the possible loss of trade secrets and the bypassing of license control mechanisms.
[src:fortran/net-framework] To mitigate this, Microsoft has included Dotfuscator Community Edition with Visual Studio .NET since 2002.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Third-party obfuscation tools are also available from vendors such as VMware, V.i.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Method-level encryption tools for .NET code are available from vendors such as SafeNet.
[src:fortran/net-framework] CLR frees the developer from the burden of managing memory (allocating and freeing up when done); it handles memory management itself by detecting when memory can be safely freed.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Instantiations of .NET types (objects) are allocated from the managed heap; a pool of memory managed by CLR.
[src:fortran/net-framework] As long as a reference to an object exists, which may be either direct, or via a graph of objects, the object is considered to be in use.
[src:fortran/net-framework] When no reference to an object exists, and it cannot be reached or used, it becomes garbage, eligible for collection.
[src:fortran/net-framework] .NET Framework includes a garbage collector (GC) which runs periodically, on a separate thread from the application's thread, that enumerates all the unusable objects and reclaims the memory allocated to them.
[src:fortran/net-framework] It is a non-deterministic, compacting, mark-and-sweep garbage collector.
[src:fortran/net-framework] GC runs only when a set amount of memory has been used or there is enough pressure for memory on the system.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Since it is not guaranteed when the conditions to reclaim memory are reached, GC runs are non-deterministic.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Each .NET application has a set of roots, which are pointers to objects on the managed heap (*managed objects*).
[src:fortran/net-framework] These include references to static objects, objects defined as local variables or method parameters currently in scope, and objects referred to by CPU registers.
[src:fortran/net-framework] When GC runs, it pauses the application and then, for each object referred to in the root, it recursively enumerates all the objects reachable from the root objects and marks them as reachable.
[src:fortran/net-framework] It uses CLI metadata and reflection to discover the objects encapsulated by an object, and then recursively walk them.
[src:fortran/net-framework] It then enumerates all the objects on the heap (which were initially allocated contiguously) using reflection.
[src:fortran/net-framework] All objects not marked as reachable are garbage.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Since the memory held by garbage is of no consequence, it is considered free space.
[src:fortran/net-framework] However, this leaves chunks of free space between objects which were initially contiguous.
[src:fortran/net-framework] The objects are then *compacted* together to make free space on the managed heap contiguous again.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Any reference to an object invalidated by moving the object is updated by GC to reflect the new location.
[src:fortran/net-framework] The application is resumed after garbage collection ends.
[src:fortran/net-framework] The latest version of .NET framework uses concurrent garbage collection along with user code, making pauses unnoticeable, because it is done in the background.
[src:fortran/net-framework] The garbage collector used by .NET Framework is also *generational*.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Newly created objects are tagged *Generation 0*.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Objects that survive one garbage collection are tagged *Generation 1*.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Generation 1 objects that survive another collection are *Generation 2*.
[src:fortran/net-framework] The framework uses up to Generation 2 objects.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Higher generation objects are garbage collected less often than lower generation objects.
[src:fortran/net-framework] This raises the efficiency of garbage collection, as older objects tend to have longer lifetimes than newer objects.
[src:fortran/net-framework] By ignoring older objects in most collection runs, fewer checks and compaction operations are needed in total.
[src:fortran/net-framework] When an application is first launched, the .NET Framework compiles the CIL code into executable code using its just-in-time compiler, and caches the executable program into the .NET Native Image Cache.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Due to caching, the application launches faster for subsequent launches, although the first launch is usually slower.
[src:fortran/net-framework] To speed up the first launch, developers may use the Native Image Generator utility to manually ahead-of-time compile and cache any .NET application.
[src:fortran/net-framework] The garbage collector, which is integrated into the environment, can introduce unanticipated delays of execution over which the developer has little direct control.
[src:fortran/net-framework] .NET Framework provides support for calling Streaming SIMD Extensions (SSE) via managed code from April 2014 in Visual Studio 2013 Update 2.
[src:fortran/net-framework] However, Mono has provided support for SIMD Extensions as of version 2.2 within the Mono.Simd namespace in 2009.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Mono's lead developer Miguel de Icaza has expressed hope that this SIMD support will be adopted by CLR's ECMA standard.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Streaming SIMD Extensions have been available in x86 CPUs since the introduction of the Pentium III.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Some other architectures such as ARM and MIPS also have SIMD extensions.
[src:fortran/net-framework] In case the CPU lacks support for those extensions, the instructions are simulated in software.
[src:fortran/net-framework] .NET Framework was the predominant implementation of CLI, until the release of .NET.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Other implementations for parts of the framework exist.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Although the runtime engine is described by an ECMA-ISO specification, other implementations of it may be encumbered by patent issues; ISO standards may include the disclaimer, "Attention is drawn to the possibility that some of the elements of this document may be the subject of patent rights.
[src:fortran/net-framework] ISO shall not be held responsible for identifying any or all such patent rights." It is harder to develop alternatives to FCL, which is not described by an open standard and may be subject to copyright restrictions.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Also, parts of FCL have Windows-specific functions and behavior, so implementation on non-Windows platforms can be problematic.
[src:fortran/net-framework] Some alternative implementations of parts of the framework are listed here.
